var acts=[{act:1,scenes:[{scene:1,name:"Scene I",setting:"Elsinore. A platform before the castle. Night.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:"FRANCISCO on his post. Enter to him BERNARDO (left hand)"},{character:"bernardo",line:"Who's there?"},{character:"francisco",line:"(right) Nay, answer me:<a href='#footnote-1' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>1</sup></a> stand, and unfold<a href='#footnote-2' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>2</sup></a> yourself."},{character:"bernardo",line:"Long live the king!<a href='#footnote-3' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>3</sup></a>"},{character:"francisco",line:"Bernardo?"},{character:"bernardo",line:"He."},{character:"francisco",line:"You come most carefully upon your hour."},{character:"bernardo",line:"'Tis now struck twelve; get thee to bed, Francisco."},{character:"francisco",line:"For this relief much thanks:"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Crosses to left]"},{character:"francisco",line:"'tis bitter cold,<br>And I am sick at heart."},{character:"bernardo",line:"Have you had quiet guard?"},{character:"francisco",line:"Not a mouse stirring."},{character:"bernardo",line:"Well, good night.<br>If you do meet Horatio and Marcellus,<br>The rivals of my watch,<a href='#footnote-4' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>4</sup></a> bid them make haste."},{character:"francisco",line:"I think I hear them.&mdash;Stand, ho! Who's there?"},{character:"horatio",line:"Friends to this ground."},{character:"marcellus",line:"And liegemen to the Dane.<a href='#footnote-5' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>5</sup></a>"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter HORATIO and MARCELLUS (left hand)"},{character:"francisco",line:"Give you good night."},{character:"marcellus",line:"O, farewell, honest soldier:<br>Who hath reliev'd you?"},{character:"francisco",line:"Bernardo hath my place.<br>Give you good night."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter HORATIO and MARCELLUS (left hand)"},{character:"marcellus",line:"Holloa! Bernardo!"},{character:"bernardo",line:"Say,<br>What, is Horatio there?"},{character:"horatio",line:"(Crosses to center) A piece of him.<a href='#footnote-6' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>6</sup></a>"},{character:"bernardo",line:"(right) Welcome, Horatio: welcome, good Marcellus."},{character:"horatio",line:"What, has this thing appear'd again to-night?"},{character:"bernardo",line:"I have seen nothing."},{character:"marcellus",line:"(left) Horatio says, 'tis but our fantasy,<br>And will not let belief take hold of him,<br>Touching this dreaded sight, twice seen of us:<br>Therefore I have entreated him, along<br>With us, to watch the minutes of this night;<a href='#footnote-7' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>7</sup></a><br>That, if again this apparition come,<br>He may approve our eyes,<a href='#footnote-8' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>8</sup></a> and speak to it."},{character:"horatio",line:"Tush! tush! 'twill not appear."},{character:"bernardo",line:"Come, let us once again assail your ears,<br>That are so fortified against our story,<br>What we two nights have seen.<a href='#footnote-9' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>9</sup></a>"},{character:"horatio",line:"Well, let us hear Bernardo speak of this."},{character:"bernardo",line:"Last night of all,<br>When yon same star that's westward from the pole<br>Had made his course to illume that part of heaven<br>Where now it burns, Marcellus, and myself,<br>The bell then beating one&mdash;"},{character:"marcellus",line:"Peace, break thee off; look, where it comes again!"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter Ghost (left hand)"},{character:"bernardo",line:"In the same figure, like the king that's dead."},{character:"horatio",line:"Most like:&mdash;it harrows me with fear and wonder.<a href='#footnote-10' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>10</sup></a>"},{character:"bernardo",line:"It would be spoke to."},{character:"marcellus",line:"Speak to it, Horatio."},{character:"horatio",line:"What art thou, that usurp'st this time of night,<a href='#footnote-11' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>11</sup></a><br>Together with that fair and warlike form<br>In which the majesty of buried Denmark<br>Did sometimes march? By heaven I charge thee, speak!"},{character:"marcellus",line:"It is offended."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Ghost crosses to right]"},{character:"bernardo",line:"See! it stalks away!"},{character:"horatio",line:"Stay!&mdash;speak!&mdash;speak, I charge thee, speak!"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exit Ghost, right hand]"},{character:"marcellus",line:"'Tis gone, and will not answer."},{character:"bernardo",line:"How now, Horatio! You tremble, and look pale:<br>Is not this something more than fantasy?<br>What think you of it?"},{character:"horatio",line:"Before heaven, I might not this believe,<br>Without the sensible and true avouch<a href='#footnote-12' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>12</sup></a><br>Of mine own eyes."},{character:"marcellus",line:"Is it not like the king?"},{character:"horatio",line:"As thou art to thyself:<br>Such was the very armour he had on,<br>When he the ambitious Norway combated."},{character:"marcellus",line:"Thus, twice before, and jump at this dead hour,<a href='#footnote-13' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>13</sup></a><br>With martial stalk hath he gone by our watch."},{character:"horatio",line:"In what particular thought to work,<a href='#footnote-14' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>14</sup></a> I know not;<br>But in the gross and scope<a href='#footnote-15' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>15</sup></a> of mine opinion,<br>This bodes some strange eruption to our state.<a href='#footnote-16' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>16</sup></a><br>In the most high and palmy<a href='#footnote-17' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>17</sup></a> state of Rome,<br>A little ere the mightiest Julius fell,<br>The graves stood tenantless, and the sheeted dead<br>Did squeak and gibber in the Roman streets."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Re-enter Ghost (right hand)]"},{character:"horatio",line:"But, (left center) soft, behold! lo, where it comes again!<br>I'll cross it, though it blast me."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[HORATIO crosses in front of the Ghost to right<br>Ghost crosses to left]"},{character:"horatio",line:"Stay, illusion!<br>If thou hast any sound, or use of voice,<a href='#footnote-18' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>18</sup></a><br>Speak to me:<br>If there be any good thing to be done,<br>That may to thee do ease, and grace to me,<br>Speak to me:<br>If thou art privy to thy country's fate,<br>Which, happily, foreknowing may avoid,<br>O, speak!<br>O, if thou hast uphoarded in thy life<br>Extorted treasure in the womb of earth,<a href='#footnote-19' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>19</sup></a><br>For which, they say, you spirits oft walk in death,<br>Speak of it:&mdash;stay, and speak!"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exit Ghost, left hand]"},{character:"marcellus",line:"'Tis gone!<br>We do it wrong, being so majestical,<br>To offer it the show of violence."},{character:"bernardo",line:"It was about to speak, when the cock crew."},{character:"horatio",line:"And then it started like a guilty thing<br>Upon a fearful summons.<a href='#footnote-20' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>20</sup></a> I have heard,<br>The cock, that is the trumpet of the morn,<br>Doth with his lofty<a href='#footnote-21' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>21</sup></a> and shrill-sounding throat<br>Awake the god of day; and, at his warning,<br>Whether in sea or fire, in earth or air,<br>The extravagant and erring spirit<a href='#footnote-22' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>22</sup></a> hies<br>To his confine.<br>But, look, the morn, in russet mantle clad,<br>Walks o'er the dew of yon high eastern hill:<br>Break we our watch up; and, by my advice,<br>Let us impart what we have seen to-night<br>Unto young Hamlet; for, upon my life,<br>This spirit, dumb to us, will speak to him."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exeunt, left hand]"}]},{scene:2,name:"Scene II",setting:"A room of state in the palace.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Trumpet March.<br>Enter the KING and QUEEN, preceded by POLONIUS, HAMLET, LAERTES,<a href='#footnote-23' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>23</sup></a> Lords, Ladies, and Attendants."},{character:"king",line:"(right center) Though yet of Hamlet our dear brother's death<br>The memory be green;<a href='#footnote-24' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>24</sup></a> and that it us befitted<br>To bear our hearts in grief, and our whole kingdom<br>To be contracted in one brow of woe;<br>Yet so far hath discretion fought with nature,<br>That we with wisest sorrow<a href='#footnote-25' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>25</sup></a> think on him,<br>Together with remembrance of ourselves.<br>Therefore our sometime sister, now our queen,<br>The imperial jointress of this warlike state,<br>Have we, as 'twere with a defeated joy,<a href='#footnote-26' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>26</sup></a><br>Taken to wife: nor have we herein barr'd<a href='#footnote-27' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>27</sup></a><br>Your better wisdoms, which have freely gone<br>With this affair along:&mdash;For all, our thanks.<br>And now, Laertes, what's the news with you?<br>You told us of some suit; What is't, Laertes?"},{character:"laertes",line:"(right) My dread lord,<br>Your leave and favour<a href='#footnote-28' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>28</sup></a> to return to France;<br>From whence though willingly I came to Denmark,<br>To show my duty in your coronation,<br>Yet now, I must confess, that duty done,<br>My thoughts and wishes bend again toward France,<br>And bow them to your gracious leave and pardon."},{character:"king",line:"Have you your father's leave? What says Polonious?"},{character:"polonius",line:"(right) He hath, my lord, (wrung from me my slow leave<br>By laboursome petition; and, at last,<br>Upon his will I sealed my hard consent):<a href='#footnote-29' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>29</sup></a><br>I do beseech you, give him leave to go."},{character:"king",line:"Take thy fair hour, Laertes; time be thine,<br>And thy best graces spend it at thy will!<a href='#footnote-30' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>30</sup></a><br>But now, my cousin Hamlet, and my son,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(left) A little more than kin, and less than kind.<a href='#footnote-31' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>31</sup></a> [Aside.]"},{character:"king",line:"How is it that the clouds still hang on you?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Not so, my lord; I am too much i'the sun.<a href='#footnote-32' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>32</sup></a>"},{character:"queen",line:"(left center) Good Hamlet, cast thy nighted colour<a href='#footnote-33' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>33</sup></a> off,<br>And let thine eye look like a friend on Denmark.<br>Do not for ever with thy vailed lids<a href='#footnote-34' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>34</sup></a><br>Seek for thy noble father in the dust:<br>Thou know'st 'tis common, all that live must die,<br>Passing through nature to eternity."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ay, madam, it is common."},{character:"queen",line:"If it be,<br>Why seems it so particular with thee?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Seems, madam! nay, it is; I know not seems.<br>'Tis not alone my inky cloak, good mother,<br>Nor the dejected haviour of the visage,<br>No, nor the fruitful river in the eye,<br>Together with all forms, modes, shows of grief,<br>That can denote me truly: These, indeed, seem,<br>For they are actions that a man might play.<br>But I have that within which passeth show;<a href='#footnote-35' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>35</sup></a><br>These but the trappings<a href='#footnote-36' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>36</sup></a> and the suits of woe."},{character:"king",line:"'Tis sweet and commendable in your nature, Hamlet,<br>To give these mourning duties to your father:<br>But, you must know, your father lost a father;<br>That father lost, lost his;<a href='#footnote-37' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>37</sup></a> and the survivor bound,<br>In filial obligation, for some term<br>To do obsequious sorrow:<a href='#footnote-38' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>38</sup></a> But to perséver<a href='#footnote-39' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>39</sup></a><br>In obstinate condolement,<a href='#footnote-40' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>40</sup></a> is a course<br>Of impious stubbornness; 'tis unmanly grief:<br>It shows a will most incorrect to Heaven.<a href='#footnote-41' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>41</sup></a><br>We pray you, throw to earth<br>This unprevailing<a href='#footnote-42' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>42</sup></a> woe; and think of us<br>As of a father: for let the world take note,<br>You are the most immediate to our throne;<br>Our chiefest courtier, cousin, and our son."},{character:"queen",line:"Let not thy mother lose her prayers, Hamlet:<br>I pray thee, stay with us; go not to Wittenberg."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I shall in all my best obey you, madam."},{character:"king",line:"Why, 'tis a loving and a fair reply;<br>Be as ourself in Denmark.&mdash;Madam, come;<br>This gentle and unforc'd accord of Hamlet<br>Sits smiling to my heart:<a href='#footnote-43' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>43</sup></a> in grace whereof,<a href='#footnote-44' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>44</sup></a><br>No jocund health that Denmark drinks to-day,<a href='#footnote-45' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>45</sup></a><br>But the great cannon to the clouds shall tell;<br>Re-speaking earthly thunder."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Trumpet March repeated. Exeunt KING and QUEEN, preceded by POLONIUS, Lords, Ladies, LAERTES, and Attendants, right hand]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"O, that this too, too solid flesh would melt,<br>Thaw, and resolve itself<a href='#footnote-46' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>46</sup></a> into a dew!<br>Or that the Everlasting had not fix'd<br>His canon<a href='#footnote-47' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>47</sup></a> 'gainst self-slaughter! O God! O God!<br>How weary, stale, flat, and unprofitable<br>Seem to me all the uses of this world!<a href='#footnote-48' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>48</sup></a><br>Fye on't! O fye! 'tis an unweeded garden,<br>That grows to seed; things rank and gross in nature<br>Possess it merely.<a href='#footnote-49' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>49</sup></a> That it should come to this!<br>But two months dead!&mdash;nay, not so much, not two:<br>So excellent a king; that was, to this,<br>Hyperion to a satyr:<a href='#footnote-50' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>50</sup></a> so loving to my mother,<br>That he might not beteem<a href='#footnote-51' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>51</sup></a> the winds of heaven<br>Visit her face too roughly. Heaven and earth!<br>Must I remember? why, she would hang on him,<br>As if increase of appetite had grown<br>By what it fed on: And yet, within a month,&mdash;<br>Let me not think on't,&mdash;Frailty, thy name is Woman!&mdash;<br>A little month; or ere those shoes were old<br>With which she follow'd my poor father's body,<br>Like Niobe, all tears;&mdash;she married with my uncle,<br>My father's brother; but no more like my father<br>Than I to Hercules.<br>It is not, nor it cannot come to, good:<br>But break, my heart, for I must hold my tongue!"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter HORATIO, BERNARDO, and MARCELLUS (right hand)"},{character:"horatio",line:"Hail to your lordship!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"I am glad to see you well:<br>Horatio,&mdash;or I do forget myself."},{character:"horatio",line:"The same, my lord, and your poor servant ever."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Sir, my good friend; I'll change that name with you:<a href='#footnote-52' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>52</sup></a><br>And what make you from Wittenberg, Horatio?&mdash;<br>Marcellus? [Crosses to center]"},{character:"marcellus",line:"(right) My good lord,"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) I am very glad to see you; good even, sir. [To BERNARDO, right]<br>But what, in faith,<a href='#footnote-53' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>53</sup></a> make you<a href='#footnote-54' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>54</sup></a> from Wittenberg?<a href='#footnote-55' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>55</sup></a>"},{character:"horatio",line:"(left) A truant disposition, good my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I would not hear your enemy say so;<br>Nor shall you do mine ear that violence,<br>To make it truster of your own report<br>Against yourself: I know you are no truant.<br>But what is your affair in Elsinore?<br>We'll teach you to drink deep, ere you depart."},{character:"horatio",line:"My lord, I came to see your father's funeral."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I pray thee, do not mock me, fellow-student;<br>I think it was to see my mother's wedding."},{character:"horatio",line:"Indeed, my lord, it followed hard upon."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Thrift, thrift, Horatio! the funeral bak'd meats<br>Did coldly furnish forth the marriage tables.<br>Would I had met my dearest foe<a href='#footnote-56' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>56</sup></a> in Heaven<br>Ere ever I had seen that day, Horatio!<br>My father,&mdash;Methinks, I see my father."},{character:"horatio",line:"Where,<br>My lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"In my mind's eye, Horatio."},{character:"horatio",line:"I saw him once; he was a goodly king.<a href='#footnote-57' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>57</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"He was a man, take him for all in all,<br>I shall not look upon his like again. [Crosses to left]"},{character:"horatio",line:"(center) My lord, I think I saw him yesternight."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Saw who?"},{character:"horatio",line:"My lord, the king your father."},{character:"hamlet",line:"The king my father!"},{character:"horatio",line:"Season your admiration for a while<a href='#footnote-58' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>58</sup></a><br>With an attent ear; till I may deliver,<br>Upon the witness of these gentlemen,<br>This marvel to you."},{character:"hamlet",line:"For Heaven's love, let me hear."},{character:"horatio",line:"Two nights together had these gentlemen,<br>Marcellus and Bernardo, on their watch,<br>In the dead waste and middle of the night,<a href='#footnote-59' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>59</sup></a><br>Been thus encounter'd. A figure like your father,<br>Arm'd at all points exactly, cap-à-pé,<br>Appears before them, and, with solemn march<br>Goes slow and stately by them: thrice he walk'd<br>By their oppress'd and fear-surprisèd eyes,<br>Within his truncheon's length; whilst they, distill'd<br>Almost to jelly with the act of fear,<a href='#footnote-60' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>60</sup></a><br>Stand dumb, and speak not to him. This to me<br>In dreadful secrecy impart they did;<br>And I with them the third night kept the watch:<br>Where, as they had deliver'd, both in time,<br>Form of the thing, each word made true and good,<br>The apparition comes."},{character:"hamlet",line:"But where was this? [Crosses to MARCELLUS.]"},{character:"marcellus",line:"(right) My lord, upon the platform where we<br>watch'd."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Did you not speak to it?"},{character:"horatio",line:"(left) My lord, I did;<br>But answer made it none: yet once methought<br>It lifted up its head, and did address<a href='#footnote-61' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>61</sup></a><br>Itself to motion, like as it would speak:<br>But, even then, the morning cock crew loud,<br>And at the sound it shrunk in haste away;<br>And vanish'd from our sight."},{character:"hamlet",line:"'Tis very strange."},{character:"horatio",line:"As I do live, my honour'd lord, 'tis true;<br>And we did think it writ down<a href='#footnote-62' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>62</sup></a> in our duty<br>To let you know of it."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Indeed, indeed, sirs, but this troubles me.<br>Hold you the watch to-night?"},{character:"marcellus",line:"We do, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Arm'd, say you?"},{character:"marcellus",line:"Arm'd, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"From top to toe?"},{character:"marcellus",line:"My lord, from head to foot."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Then saw you not<br>His face?"},{character:"horatio",line:"O, yes, my lord; he wore his beaver up.<a href='#footnote-63' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>63</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"What, looked he frowningly?"},{character:"horatio",line:"A countenance more<br>In sorrow than in anger."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Pale or red?"},{character:"horatio",line:"Nay, very pale."},{character:"hamlet",line:"And fix'd his eyes upon you?"},{character:"horatio",line:"Most constantly."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I would I had been there."},{character:"horatio",line:"It would have much amaz'd you."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Very like,<br>Very like. Stay'd it long?"},{character:"horatio",line:"While one with moderate haste might tell a hundred."},{character:"marcellus, bernardo",line:"Longer, Longer."},{character:"horatio",line:"Not when I saw it."},{character:"hamlet",line:"His beard was grizzl'd, No?"},{character:"horatio",line:"It was, as I have seen it in his life,<br>A sable silver'd."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I will watch to-night;<br>Perchance, 'twill walk again."},{character:"horatio",line:"(center) I warrant it will."},{character:"hamlet",line:"If it assume my noble father's person,<br>I'll speak to it, though hell itself should gape,<br>And bid me hold my peace. [Crosses to left] I pray you all,<br>If you have hitherto conceal'd this sight,<br>Let it be tenable<a href='#footnote-64' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>64</sup></a> in your silence still;<br>And whatsoever else shall hap to-night,<br>Give it an understanding, but no tongue;<br>I will requite your loves. So, fare you well:<br>Upon the platform, 'twixt eleven and twelve,<br>I'll visit you."},{character:"horatio",line:"(right) Our duty to your honour."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Your loves, as mine to you: Farewell."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exeunt HORATIO, MARCELLUS, and BERNARDO, right hand]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"My father's spirit in arms! all is not well;<br>I doubt some foul play: 'would the night were come;<br>Till then sit still, my soul: Foul deeds will rise,<br>Though all the earth o'erwhelm them, to men's eyes."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exit, left hand]"}]},{scene:3,name:"Scene III",setting:"A room in Polonius's house.",lines:[{character:"laertes",line:"(left center) My necessaries are embarked: farewell:<br>And, sister, as the winds give benefit,<a href='#footnote-65' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>65</sup></a><br>Let me hear from you."},{character:"ophelia",line:"(right center) Do you doubt that?"},{character:"laertes",line:"For Hamlet, and the trifling of his favour,<a href='#footnote-66' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>66</sup></a><br>Hold it a fashion, and a toy in blood;<br>A violet in the youth of primy nature,<br>Forward, not permanent, sweet, not lasting,<br>The pérfume and suppliance of a minute.<a href='#footnote-67' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>67</sup></a>"},{character:"ophelia",line:"No more but so?"},{character:"laertes",line:"He may not, as unvalued persons do,<br>Carve for himself; for on his choice depends<br>The safety and the health of the whole state.<br>Then weigh what loss your honour may sustain,<br>If with too credent ear you list his songs.<br>Fear it, Ophelia, fear it, my dear sister;<br>And keep within the rear of your affection,<a href='#footnote-68' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>68</sup></a><br>Out of the shot and danger of desire.<br>The chariest maid<a href='#footnote-69' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>69</sup></a> is prodigal enough,<br>If she unmask her beauty to the moon:<br>Virtue itself scapes not calumnious strokes:<br>Be wary, then; best safety lies in fear:<br>Youth to itself rebels, though none else near."},{character:"ophelia",line:"I shall the effect of this good lesson keep,<br>As watchman to my heart. But, good my brother,<br>Do not, as some ungracious pastors do,<br>Show me the steep and thorny way to heaven<br>Whilst, like a puff'd and reckless libertine,<a href='#footnote-70' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>70</sup></a><br>Himself the primrose path of dalliance treads,<br>And recks not his own read.<a href='#footnote-71' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>71</sup></a>"},{character:"laertes",line:"O, fear me not.<br>I stay too long;&mdash;but here my father comes."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"_Enter_ POLONIUS (left hand)"},{character:"polonius",line:"Yet here, Laertes! aboard, aboard, for shame!<br>The wind sits in the shoulder of your sail,<a href='#footnote-72' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>72</sup></a><br>And you are staid for. There,&mdash;my blessing with you! [_Laying his hand on_ LAERTES' _head_.]<br>And these few precepts in thy memory&mdash;<br>Look thou charácter.<a href='#footnote-73' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>73</sup></a> Give thy thoughts no tongue,<br>Nor any unproportion'd thought<a href='#footnote-74' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>74</sup></a> his act.<br>Be thou familiar, but by no means vulgar.<br>The friends thou hast, and their adoption tried,<br>Grapple them to thy soul with hooks of steel;<br>But do not dull thy palm with entertainment<br>Of each new-hatch'd, unfledg'd comrade. Beware<br>Of entrance to a quarrel; but being in,<br>Bear it, that the opposer may beware of thee.<br>Give every man thine ear, but few thy voice:<br>Take each man's censure,<a href='#footnote-75' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>75</sup></a> but reserve thy judgment.<br>Costly thy habit as thy purse can buy,<br>But not express'd in fancy; rich, not gaudy:<br>For the apparel oft proclaims the man;<br>And they in France of the best rank and station<br>Are most select and generous, chief in that.<a href='#footnote-76' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>76</sup></a><br>Neither a borrower nor a lender be:<br>For loan oft loses both itself and friend;<br>And borrowing dulls the edge of husbandry.<a href='#footnote-77' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>77</sup></a><br>This above all,&mdash;To thine ownself be true;<br>And it must follow, as the night the day,<br>Thou canst not then be false to any man.<br>Farewell; my blessing season this in thee!<a href='#footnote-78' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>78</sup></a>"},{character:"laertes",line:"Most humbly do I take my leave, my lord. [_Crosses to_ left]<br>Farewell, Ophelia; and remember well<br>What I have said to you."},{character:"ophelia",line:"(_Crosses to_ LAERTES.) 'Tis in my memory lock'd,<br>And you yourself shall keep the key of it.<a href='#footnote-79' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>79</sup></a>"},{character:"laertes",line:"Farewell. [_Exit_ LAERTES, left hand]"},{character:"polonius",line:"What is it, Ophelia, he hath said to you?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"So please you, something touching the lord Hamlet."},{character:"polonius",line:"Marry, well bethought:<br>'Tis told me, he hath very oft of late<br>Given private time to you;<a href='#footnote-80' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>80</sup></a> and you yourself<br>Have of your audience been most free and bounteous:<br>If it be so (as so 'tis put on me,<a href='#footnote-81' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>81</sup></a><br>And that in way of caution), I must tell you,<br>You do not understand yourself so clearly<br>As it behoves my daughter, and your honour.<br>What is between<a href='#footnote-82' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>82</sup></a> you? give me up the truth."},{character:"ophelia",line:"He hath, my lord, of late, made many tenders<br>Of his affection to me."},{character:"polonius",line:"Affection! pooh! you speak like a green girl,<br>Unsifted<a href='#footnote-83' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>83</sup></a> in such perilous circumstance.<br>Do you believe his tenders, as you call them?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"I do not know, my lord, what I should think."},{character:"polonius",line:"Marry, I'll teach you: think yourself a baby;<br>That you have ta'en these tenders for true pay,<br>Which are not sterling. Tender yourself more dearly;<br>Or, you'll tender me a fool."},{character:"ophelia",line:"My lord, he hath impórtun'd me with love<br>In honourable fashion."},{character:"polonius",line:"Ay, fashion you may call it; go to, go to."},{character:"ophelia",line:"And hath given countenance to his speech, my lord,<br>With almost all the holy vows of heaven."},{character:"polonius",line:"Ay, springes to catch woodcocks.<a href='#footnote-84' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>84</sup></a> I do know,<br>When the blood burns, how prodigal the soul<br>Lends the tongue vows: This is for all,&mdash;<br>I would not, in plain terms, from this time forth,<br>Have you so slander any leisure moment,<a href='#footnote-85' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>85</sup></a><br>As to give words or talk with the lord Hamlet.<br>Look to't, I charge you: come your ways."},{character:"ophelia",line:"I shall obey, my lord."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[_Exeunt_, right hand]"}]},{scene:4,name:"Scene IV",setting:"The platform. Night.",lines:[{character:"hamlet",line:"The air bites shrewdly; it is very cold."},{character:"horatio",line:"It is a nipping and an eager air.<a href='#footnote-86' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>86</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"What hour now?"},{character:"horatio",line:"I think it lacks of twelve."},{character:"marcellus",line:"No, it is struck."},{character:"horatio",line:"(right center) Indeed? I heard it not: then it draws near the season,<br>Wherein the spirit held his wont to walk."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[A Flourish of Trumpets, and Ordnance shot off without.]"},{character:"horatio",line:"What does this mean, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(left center) The king doth wake to-night,<a href='#footnote-87' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>87</sup></a> and takes his rouse,<a href='#footnote-88' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>88</sup></a><br>And, as he drains his draughts of Rhenish down,<br>The kettle-drum and trumpet thus bray out<br>The triumph of his pledge."},{character:"horatio",line:"Is it a custom?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ay, marry, is't: [Crosses to HORATIO.]<br>But to my mind,&mdash;though I am native here,<br>And to the manner born,&mdash;it is a custom<br>More honour'd in the breach than the observance. Enter Ghost (left hand)"},{character:"horatio",line:"(right hand) Look, my lord, it comes!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Angels and ministers of grace defend us!&mdash;<br>Be thou a spirit of health or goblin damn'd,<br>Bring with thee airs from heaven or blasts from hell,<br>Be thy intents wicked or charitable,<br>Thou com'st in such a questionable shape,<a href='#footnote-89' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>89</sup></a><br>That I will speak to thee: I'll call thee&mdash;Hamlet,<br>King, father: Royal Dane: O, answer me!<br>Let me not burst in ignorance; but tell<br>Why thy canoniz'd bones, hearsed in death,<a href='#footnote-90' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>90</sup></a><br>Have burst their cerements;<a href='#footnote-91' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>91</sup></a> why the sepulchre,<br>Wherein we saw thee quietly in-urn'd,<br>Hath op'd his ponderous and marble jaws,<br>To cast thee up again! What may this mean,<br>That thou, dead corse, again, in cómplete steel,<br>Revisits thus the glimpses of the moon,<br>Making night hideous; and we fools of nature<a href='#footnote-92' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>92</sup></a><br>So horridly to shake our disposition<a href='#footnote-93' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>93</sup></a><br>With thoughts beyond the reaches of our souls?<br>Say, why is this? wherefore? what should we do? [Ghost beckons.]"},{character:"horatio",line:"It beckons you to go away with it,<br>As if it some impartment did desire<br>To you alone. [Ghost beckons again.]"},{character:"marcellus",line:"Look, with what courteous action<br>It waves you to a more removèd ground:<a href='#footnote-94' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>94</sup></a><br>But do not go with it."},{character:"horatio",line:"No, by no means."},{character:"hamlet",line:"It will not speak; then I will follow it."},{character:"horatio",line:"Do not, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why, what should be the fear?<br>I do not set my life at a pin's fee;<a href='#footnote-95' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>95</sup></a><br>And for my soul, what can it do to that,<br>Being a thing immortal as itself? [Ghost beckons.]<br>It waves me forth again;&mdash;I'll follow it."},{character:"horatio",line:"What if it tempt you toward the flood, my lord,<a href='#footnote-96' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>96</sup></a><br>Or to the dreadful summit of the cliff<br>That beetles o'er his base into the sea,<a href='#footnote-97' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>97</sup></a><br>And there assume some other horrible form,<br>And draw you into madness? [Ghost beckons.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"It waves me still.&mdash;<br>Go on; I'll follow thee."},{character:"marcellus",line:"You shall not go, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Hold off your hands."},{character:"horatio",line:"Be rul'd; you shall not go."},{character:"hamlet",line:"My fate cries out,<br>And makes each petty artery in this body<br>As hardy as the Némean lion's nerve.<a href='#footnote-98' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>98</sup></a> [Ghost beckons]<br>Still am I call'd:&mdash;unhand me, gentlemen; [Breaking from them.]<br>By heaven, I'll make a ghost of him that lets me:&mdash;<a href='#footnote-99' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>99</sup></a><br>I say, away!&mdash;Go on; I'll follow thee."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exeunt Ghost and HAMLET, left hand, followed at a distance by HORATIO and MARCELLUS.]"}]},{scene:5,name:"Scene V",setting:"A more remote part of the platform. Night.",lines:[{character:"hamlet",line:"(right) Whither wilt thou lead me? Speak; I'll go no further."},{character:"ghost",line:"(left) Mark me."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I will."},{character:"ghost",line:"My hour is almost come,<br>When I to sulphurous and tormenting flames<br>Must render up myself."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Alas, poor ghost!"},{character:"ghost",line:"Pity me not, but lend thy serious hearing<br>To what I shall unfold."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Speak; I am bound to hear."},{character:"ghost",line:"So art thou to revenge, when thou shalt hear."},{character:"hamlet",line:"What?"},{character:"ghost",line:"I am thy father's spirit;<br>Doom'd for a certain term to walk the night,<br>And for the day confin'd to fast in fires,<a href='#footnote-100' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>100</sup></a><br>Till the foul crimes done in my days of nature<br>Are burnt and purg'd away. But that I am forbid<br>To tell the secrets of my prison-house,<br>I could a tale unfold, whose lightest word<br>Would harrow up thy soul;<a href='#footnote-101' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>101</sup></a> freeze thy young blood;<br>Make thy two eyes, like stars, start from their spheres;<br>Thy knotted and combinèd locks to part,<br>And each particular hair to stand on end,<a href='#footnote-102' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>102</sup></a><br>Like quills upon the fretful porcupine:<a href='#footnote-103' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>103</sup></a><br>But this eternal blazon<a href='#footnote-104' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>104</sup></a> must not be<br>To ears of flesh and blood.&mdash;List, list, O, list!&mdash;<br>If thou didst ever thy dear father love,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"hamlet",line:"O Heaven!"},{character:"ghost",line:"Revenge his foul and most unnatural murder."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Murder!"},{character:"ghost",line:"Murder most foul, as in the best it is;<br>But this most foul, strange, and unnatural."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Haste me to know it, that I, with wings as swift<br>As meditation or the thoughts of love,<br>May sweep to my revenge."},{character:"ghost",line:"I find thee apt;<br>And duller shouldst thou be than the fat weed<br>That rots itself in ease on Lethe wharf,<a href='#footnote-105' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>105</sup></a><br>Wouldst thou not stir in this. Now, Hamlet, hear:<br>'Tis given out that, sleeping in mine orchard,<a href='#footnote-106' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>106</sup></a><br>A serpent stung me; so the whole ear of Denmark<br>Is by a forged process<a href='#footnote-107' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>107</sup></a> of my death<br>Rankly abus'd: but know, thou noble youth,<br>The serpent that did sting thy father's life<br>Now wears his crown."},{character:"hamlet",line:"O, my prophetic soul! my uncle!"},{character:"ghost",line:"Ay, that incestuous, that adulterate beast,<br>With witchcraft of his wit, with traitorous gifts,<br>Won to his shameful lust<br>The will of my most seeming virtuous queen:<br>O, Hamlet, what a falling-off was there!<br>From me, whose love was of that dignity,<br>That it went hand in hand even with the vow<br>I made to her in marriage; and to decline<br>Upon a wretch,<a href='#footnote-108' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>108</sup></a> whose natural gifts were poor<br>To those of mine!<br>But, soft! methinks I scent the morning air;<br>Brief let me be.&mdash;Sleeping within mine orchard,<br>My custom always in the afternoon,<br>Upon my secure<a href='#footnote-109' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>109</sup></a> hour thy uncle stole,<br>With juice of cursed hebenon<a href='#footnote-110' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>110</sup></a> in a vial,<br>And in the porches of mine ears did pour<br>The leperous distilment; whose effect<br>Holds such an enmity with blood of man,<br>That, swift as quicksilver, it courses through<br>The natural gates and alleys of the body;<br>So did it mine;<br>Thus was I, sleeping, by a brother's hand<br>Of life, of crown, of queen, at once despatch'd:<a href='#footnote-111' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>111</sup></a><br>Cut off even in the blossoms of my sin,<br>Unhousel'd, disappointed, unanel'd;<a href='#footnote-112' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>112</sup></a><br>No reckoning made, but sent to my account<br>With all my imperfections on my head."},{character:"hamlet",line:"O, horrible! O, horrible! most horrible!"},{character:"ghost",line:"If thou hast nature in thee, bear it not;<br>Let not the royal bed of Denmark be<br>A couch for luxury<a href='#footnote-113' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>113</sup></a> and damnèd incest.<br>But, howsoever thou pursu'st this act,<br>Taint not thy mind, nor let thy soul contrive<br>Against thy mother aught: leave her to Heaven,<br>And to those thorns that in her bosom lodge,<br>To prick and sting her. Fare thee well at once!<br>The glow-worm shows the matin to be near,<br>And 'gins to pale his ineffectual fire:<a href='#footnote-114' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>114</sup></a><br>Adieu, adieu, adieu! remember me. [Exit, left hand]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Hold, hold, my heart;<br>And you, my sinews, grow not instant old,<br>But bear me stiffly up.&mdash;Remember thee!<br>Ay, thou poor ghost, while memory holds a seat<br>In this distracted globe.<a href='#footnote-115' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>115</sup></a> Remember thee!<br>Yea, from the table of my memory<br>I'll wipe away all forms, all pressures past,<a href='#footnote-116' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>116</sup></a><br>And thy commandment all alone shall live<br>Within the book and volume of my brain,<br>Unmix'd with baser matter: yes, by heaven,<br>I have sworn't."},{character:"horatio",line:"(Without.) My lord, my lord,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"marcellus",line:"(Without.) Lord Hamlet,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"horatio",line:"(Without.) Heaven secure him!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"So be it!"},{character:"marcellus",line:"(Without.) Illo, ho, ho, my lord!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Hillo, ho, ho, boy! come, bird, come.<a href='#footnote-117' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>117</sup></a>"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter HORATIO and MARCELLUS (left hand upper entrance)"},{character:"marcellus",line:"(right) How is't, my noble lord?"},{character:"horatio",line:"(left) What news, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) O, wonderful!"},{character:"horatio",line:"Good my lord, tell it."},{character:"hamlet",line:"No;<br>You will reveal it."},{character:"horatio",line:"Not I, my lord, by heaven."},{character:"marcellus",line:"Nor I, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How say you, then; would heart of man once think it?<br>But you'll be secret?&mdash;"},{character:"horatio, marcellus",line:"Ay, by heaven, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"There's ne'er a villain, dwelling in all Denmark&mdash;<br>But he's an arrant knave.<a href='#footnote-118' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>118</sup></a>"},{character:"horatio",line:"There needs no ghost, my lord, come from the grave<br>To tell us this."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why, right; you are in the right;<br>And so, without more circumstance at all,<br>I hold it fit that we shake hands, and part:<br>You as your business and desire shall point you,<br>For every man hath business and desire,<br>Such as it is;&mdash;and, for my own poor part,<br>Look you, I will go pray."},{character:"horatio",line:"These are but wild and whirling words,<a href='#footnote-119' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>119</sup></a> my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I am sorry they offend you, heartily."},{character:"horatio",line:"There's no offence, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Yes, by Saint Patrick,<a href='#footnote-120' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>120</sup></a> but there is, Horatio,<br>And much offence, too. Touching this vision here,<br>It is an honest ghost, that let me tell you:<br>For your desire to know what is between us,<br>O'er-master it<a href='#footnote-121' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>121</sup></a> as you may. And now, good friends,<br>As you are friends, scholars, and soldiers,<br>Give me one poor request."},{character:"horatio",line:"What is't, my lord?<br>We will."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Never make known what you have seen to-night."},{character:"horatio, marcellus",line:"My lord, we will not."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Nay, but swear't."},{character:"horatio",line:"Propose the oath, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Never to speak of this that you have seen.<br>Swear by my sword."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[HORATIO and MARCELLUS place each their right hand on HAMLET'S sword.]"},{character:"ghost",line:"(Beneath.) Swear."},{character:"horatio",line:"O day and night, but this is wondrous strange!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"And therefore as a stranger give it welcome.<a href='#footnote-122' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>122</sup></a><br>There are more things in heaven and earth, Horatio,<br>Than are dreamt of in your philosophy.<br>But come;&mdash;<br>Here, as before, never, so help you mercy,<br>How strange or odd soe'er I bear myself,<br>As I, perchance, hereafter shall think meet<br>To put an antick disposition<a href='#footnote-123' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>123</sup></a> on,&mdash;<br>That you, at such times seeing me, never shall,<br>With arms encumber'd thus,<a href='#footnote-124' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>124</sup></a> or this head-shake,<br>Or by pronouncing of some doubtful phrase,<br>As, Well, we know; or, We could, an if we would; or, If<br>we list to speak;&mdash;or, There be, an if they might;&mdash;<br>Or such ambiguous giving out, to note<br>That you know aught of me:&mdash;This do you swear,<br>So grace and mercy at your most need help you!"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[HORATIO and MARCELLUS again place their hands on HAMLET'S sword.]"},{character:"ghost",line:"(Beneath.) Swear."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Rest, rest, perturbed spirit! So gentlemen,<br>With all my love I do commend me to you:<br>And what so poor a man as Hamlet is<br>May do, to express his love and friending to you,<br>Heaven willing, shall not lack.<a href='#footnote-125' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>125</sup></a> Let us go in together; [Crosses to left]<br>And still your fingers on your lips, I pray.<br>The time is out of joint;&mdash;O cursèd spite,<br>That ever I was born to set it right!<br>Nay, come, let's go together."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exeunt left hand]"}]}]},{act:2,scenes:[{scene:1,name:"Scene I",setting:"A room in Polonius's house.",lines:[{character:"polonius",line:"How now, Ophelia! What's the matter?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"O, my lord, my lord, I have been so affrighted!"},{character:"polonius",line:"With what, in the name of Heaven?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"My lord, as I was sewing in my closet,<br>Lord Hamlet, with his doublet all unbrac'd;<br>Pale as his shirt; his knees knocking each other,<br>And with a look so piteous in purport,<br>He comes before me."},{character:"polonius",line:"Mad for thy love?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"My lord, I do not know;<br>But, truly, I do fear it."},{character:"polonius",line:"What said he?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"He took me by the wrist, and held me hard;<br>Then goes he to the length of all his arm;<br>And, with his other hand thus o'er his brow,<br>He falls to such perusal of my face<br>As he would draw it. Long staid he so;<br>At last,--a little shaking of mine arm,<br>And thrice his head thus waving up and down,<br>He rais'd a sigh so piteous and profound,<br>As it did seem to shatter all his bulk,<a href='#footnote-2' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>2</sup></a><br>And end his being: That done, he lets me go:<br>And, with his head over his shoulder turn'd,<br>He seem'd to find his way without his eyes;<br>For out o'doors he went without their helps,<br>And, to the last, bended their light on me."},{character:"polonius",line:"Come, go with me; I will go seek the king.<br>This is the very ecstacy of love;<a href='#footnote-3' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>3</sup></a><br>What, have you given him any hard words of late?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"No, my good lord; but, as you did command,<br>I did repel his letters, and denied<br>His access to me."},{character:"polonius",line:"That hath made him mad.<br>Come, go we to the king:<br>This must be known; which, being kept close, might move<br>More grief to hide than hate to utter love.<a href='#footnote-4' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>4</sup></a><br>Come."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[_Exeunt_ left hand]"}]},{scene:2,name:"Scene II",setting:"A room in the same.",lines:[{character:"king",line:"(center) Welcome, dear Rosencrantz and Guildenstern!<br>Moreover that we much did long to see you,<br>The need we have to use you did provoke<br>Our hasty sending. Something have you heard<br>Of Hamlet's transformation. What it should be,<br>More than his father's death, that thus hath put him<br>So much from the understanding of himself,<a href='#footnote-5' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>5</sup></a><br>I cannot dream of: I entreat you both,<br>That you vouchsafe your rest<a href='#footnote-6' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>6</sup></a> here in our court<br>Some little time: so by your companies<br>To draw him on to pleasures, and to gather,<br>Whether aught, to us unknown, afflicts him thus,<br>That, open'd, lies within our remedy."},{character:"queen",line:"(right center) Good gentlemen, he hath much talk'd of you;<br>And sure I am two men there are not living<br>To whom he more adheres. If it will please you<br>So to expend your time with us a while,<br>Your visitation shall receive such thanks<br>As fits a king's remembrance."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"(right) Both your majesties<br>Might, by the sovereign power you have of us,<a href='#footnote-7' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>7</sup></a><br>Put your dread pleasures more into command<br>Than to entreaty."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"(right) But we both obey,<br>And here give up ourselves, in the full bent,<a href='#footnote-8' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>8</sup></a><br>To lay our service freely at your feet."},{character:"king",line:"Thanks, Rosencrantz and gentle Guildenstern."},{character:"queen",line:"I do beseech you instantly to visit<br>My too much changèd son. Go, some of you,<br>And bring these gentlemen where Hamlet is.<br>[Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ, GUILDENSTERN, and<br>Attendants, right hand]<br>Enter POLONIUS (left hand)"},{character:"polonius",line:"Now do I think (or else this brain of mine<br>Hunts not the trail of policy<a href='#footnote-9' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>9</sup></a> so sure<br>As it hath us'd to do), that I have found<br>The very cause of Hamlet's lunacy."},{character:"king",line:"(center) O, speak of that; that do I long to hear."},{character:"polonius",line:"(left center) My liege, and madam, to expostulate<a href='#footnote-10' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>10</sup></a><br>What majesty should be, what duty is,<br>Why day is day, night night, and time is time,<br>Were nothing but to waste night, day, and time;<br>Therefore, since brevity is the soul of wit,<br>And tediousness the limbs and outward flourishes,&mdash;<br>I will be brief:&mdash;Your noble son is mad:<br>Mad call I it; for, to define true madness,<br>What is't, but to be nothing else but mad?<br>But let that go."},{character:"queen",line:"(right center) More matter, with less art."},{character:"polonius",line:"Madam, I swear I use no art at all.<br>That he is mad, 'tis true: 'tis true 'tis pity;<br>And pity 'tis, 'tis true: a foolish figure;<br>But farewell it, for I will use no art.<br>Mad let us grant him, then: and now remains<br>That we find out the cause of this effect,<br>Or, rather say, the cause of this defect,<br>For this effect defective comes by cause:<br>Thus it remains, and the remainder thus,<br>Perpend.<a href='#footnote-11' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>11</sup></a><br>I have a daughter, have, while she is mine,<br>Who, in her duty and obedience, mark,<br>Hath given me this: Now gather, and surmise.<br><br>[Reads] To the celestial, and my soul's idol, the most beautified Ophelia,&mdash;<a href='#footnote-12' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>12</sup></a><br>That's an ill phrase, a vile phrase, beautified is a vile phrase: but you shall hear. Thus:<br>In her excellent white bosom,<a href='#footnote-13' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>13</sup></a> these, &c.<a href='#footnote-14' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>14</sup></a>"},{character:"queen",line:"Came this from Hamlet to her?"},{character:"polonius",line:"Good madam, stay awhile; I will be faithful.&mdash;<br>[Reads.] Doubt thou the stars are fire;<br>Doubt thou the sun doth move;<br>Doubt truth to be a liar;<br>But never doubt, I love.<br><br>O dear Ophelia, I am ill at these numbers;<a href='#footnote-15' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>15</sup></a> I have not art to reckon my groans: but that I love thee best, O most best,<a href='#footnote-16' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>16</sup></a> believe it. Adieu.<br><br>Thine evermore, most dear lady, whilst this machine is to him,<a href='#footnote-17' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>17</sup></a> Hamlet.<br><br>This, in obedience, hath my daughter shown me:<br>And more above,<a href='#footnote-18' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>18</sup></a> hath his solicitings,<a href='#footnote-19' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>19</sup></a><br>As they fell out by time, by means, and place,<br>All given to my ear."},{character:"king",line:"But how hath she<br>Receiv'd his love?"},{character:"polonius",line:"What do you think of me?"},{character:"king",line:"As of a man faithful and honourable."},{character:"polonius",line:"I would fain prove so. But what might you think,<br>When I had seen this hot love on the wing<br>(As I perceived it, I must tell you that,<br>Before my daughter told me), what might you,<br>Or my dear majesty your queen here, think,<br>If I had play'd the desk or table book;<a href='#footnote-20' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>20</sup></a><br>Or given my heart a winking, mute and dumb;<a href='#footnote-21' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>21</sup></a><br>Or look'd upon this love with idle sight;<a href='#footnote-22' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>22</sup></a><br>What might you think? No, I went round to work,<a href='#footnote-23' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>23</sup></a><br>And my young mistress thus did I bespeak:<br>Lord Hamlet is a prince, out of thy sphere;<br>This must not be: and then I precepts gave her,<br>That she should lock herself from his resort,<br>Admit no messengers, receive no tokens.<br>Which done, she took the fruits of my advice;<a href='#footnote-24' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>24</sup></a><br>And he, repuls'd (a short tale to make),<br>Fell into sadness; thence into a weakness;<br>Thence to a lightness; and, by this declension,<br>Into the madness wherein now he raves,<br>And all we mourn for."},{character:"king",line:"Do you think 'tis this?"},{character:"queen",line:"It may be, very likely."},{character:"polonius",line:"Hath there been such a time (I'd fain know that,)<br>That I have positively said, 'tis so,<br>When it proved otherwise?"},{character:"king",line:"Not that I know."},{character:"polonius",line:"Take this from this, if it be otherwise: [Pointing to his head and shoulder.]<br>If circumstances lead me, I will find<br>Where truth is hid, though it were hid indeed<br>Within the centre."},{character:"king",line:"How may we try it further?"},{character:"polonius",line:"You know, sometimes he walks for hours together<br>Here in the lobby."},{character:"queen",line:"So he does, indeed."},{character:"polonius",line:"At such a time I'll loose my daughter to him:<br>Mark the encounter: if he love her not,<br>And be not from his reason fallen thereon,<br>Let me be no assistant for a state,<br>But keep a farm, and carters."},{character:"king",line:"We will try it."},{character:"queen",line:"But, look, where sadly the poor wretch comes reading."},{character:"polonius",line:"Away, I do beseech you both, away:<br>I'll board him presently.<a href='#footnote-25' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>25</sup></a> [Exeunt KING and QUEEN, right hand] Enter HAMLET, reading (left center)"},{character:"polonius",line:"How does my good lord Hamlet?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Excellent well."},{character:"polonius",line:"(right) Do you know me, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Excellent well; you are a fishmonger.<a href='#footnote-26' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>26</sup></a>"},{character:"polonius",line:"Not I, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Then I would you were so honest a man."},{character:"polonius",line:"Honest, my lord!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ay, sir; to be honest, as this world goes, is to be one man<br>picked out of ten thousand."},{character:"polonius",line:"That's very true, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"For if the sun breed maggots in a dead dog, being a god,<br>kissing carrion,&mdash;&mdash;Have you a daughter?<a href='#footnote-27' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>27</sup></a>"},{character:"polonius",line:"I have, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Let her not walk i'the sun: conception is a blessing; but as<br>your daughter may conceive,&mdash;friend, look to't, look to't, look to't.<br>[Goes up stage.]"},{character:"polonius",line:"(Aside.) Still harping on my daughter:&mdash;yet he knew me not<br>at first; he said I was a fishmonger. [Crosses to left] I'll speak to him again.&mdash;What do you read, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Words, words, words."},{character:"polonius",line:"(left) What is the matter, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Between who?"},{character:"polonius",line:"I mean, the matter that you read, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Slanders, sir: for the satirical rogue<a href='#footnote-28' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>28</sup></a> says here that old<br>men have grey beards; that their faces are wrinkled; their eyes<br>purging thick amber and plum-tree gum; and that they have a plentiful<br>lack of wit, together with most weak hams: All of which, sir, though<br>I most powerfully and potently believe, yet I hold it not honesty to<br>have it thus set down; for yourself, sir, shall be as old as I am,<br>if, like a crab, you could go backward.<br>[Crosses, left]"},{character:"polonius",line:"(Aside.) Though this be madness, yet there's method in it.<br>Will you walk out of the air, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Into my grave?<br>[Crosses right]"},{character:"polonius",line:"(left) Indeed, that is out o' the air.&mdash;How pregnant sometimes<br>his replies<a href='#footnote-29' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>29</sup></a> are! a happiness that often madness hits on, which<br>reason and sanity could not so prosperously be delivered of. I will<br>leave him, and suddenly contrive the means of meeting between him and<br>my daughter.&mdash;My honourable lord, I will most humbly take my leave of you."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) You cannot, sir, take from me any thing that I will more<br>willingly part withall, except my life, except my life, except my life."},{character:"polonius",line:"Fare you well, my lord.<br>[Exit POLONIUS, left hand]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"These tedious old fools!"},{character:"polonius",line:"(Without.) You go to seek the lord Hamlet; there he is."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"Heaven save you, sir! Enter ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN (left hand)"},{character:"guildenstern",line:"My honor'd lord!&mdash;"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"My most dear lord!&mdash;"},{character:"hamlet",line:"My excellent good friends! How dost thou, Guildenstern?<br>[Crosses to ROSENCRANTZ.] Ah, Rosencrantz! Good lads, how do ye both? What news?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"(left) None, my lord, but that the world's grown honest."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Then is dooms-day near: but your news is not true. In the<br>beaten way of friendship,<a href='#footnote-30' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>30</sup></a> what make you at Elsinore?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"To visit you, my lord; no other occasion."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Beggar that I am, I am even poor in thanks; but I thank you.<br>Were you not sent for? Is it your own inclining? Is it a free<br>visitation? Come, come, deal justly with me: come, come; nay, speak."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"(right) What should we say, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Any thing&mdash;but to the purpose. You were sent for; and there is<br>a kind of confession in your looks, which your modesties have not<br>craft enough to colour: I know the good king and queen have sent for you."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"To what end, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"That you must teach me. But let me conjure you, by the rights<br>of our fellowship, [taking their hands,] by the consonancy of our<br>youth,<a href='#footnote-31' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>31</sup></a> by the obligation of our ever-preserved love, and by what<br>more dear a better proposer<a href='#footnote-32' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>32</sup></a> could charge you withal, be even<a href='#footnote-33' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>33</sup></a><br>and direct with me, whether you were sent for, or no?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"What say you?<br>[To GUILDENSTERN.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Nay, then, I have an eye of you.<a href='#footnote-34' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>34</sup></a><br>[Crosses right]<br>[Aside.] &mdash;if you love me, hold not off."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"My lord, we were sent for."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(Returning center) I will tell you why; so shall my anticipation<br>prevent your discovery, and your secrecy to the king and queen moult<br>no feather.<a href='#footnote-35' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>35</sup></a> I have of late (but wherefore I know not) lost all my<br>mirth, forgone all custom of exercises; and, indeed, it goes so<br>heavily with my disposition, that this goodly frame, the earth, seems<br>to me a steril promontory; this most excellent canopy, the air, look<br>you, this brave o'erhanging firmament, this majestical roof fretted<br>with golden fire, why, it appears no other thing to me than a foul<br>and pestilent congregation of vapours. What a piece of work is man!<br>How noble in reason! how infinite in faculties! in form and moving<br>how express<a href='#footnote-36' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>36</sup></a> and admirable! in action how like an angel! in<br>apprehension how like a god! the beauty of the world! the paragon<a href='#footnote-37' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>37</sup></a><br>of animals! And yet, to me, what is this quintessence of dust? man<br>delights not me,&mdash;nor woman neither, though by your smiling you seem<br>to say so."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"My lord, there was no such stuff in my thoughts."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why did you laugh, then, when I said, Man delights not me?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"To think, my lord, if you delight not in man, what lenten<br>entertainment<a href='#footnote-38' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>38</sup></a> the players shall receive from you: we coted them<br>on the way;<a href='#footnote-39' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>39</sup></a> and hither are they coming, to offer you service."},{character:"hamlet",line:"He that plays the king shall be welcome, his majesty shall<br>have tribute of me; the adventurous knight shall use his foil and<br>target; the lover shall not sigh gratis; the humorous man shall end<br>his part in peace;<a href='#footnote-40' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>40</sup></a> and the lady shall say her mind freely, or the<br>blank verse shall halt for't.<a href='#footnote-41' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>41</sup></a>&mdash;What players are they?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"Even those you were wont to take such delight in, the tragedians of the city."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How chances it, they travel?<a href='#footnote-42' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>42</sup></a> their residence, both in<br>reputation and profit, was better both ways. Do they hold the same<br>estimation they did when I was in the city? Are they so followed?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"No, indeed, they are not."},{character:"hamlet",line:"It is not very strange; for my uncle is king of Denmark,<a href='#footnote-43' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>43</sup></a><br>and those that would make mouths at him<a href='#footnote-44' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>44</sup></a> while my father lived,<br>give twenty, forty, fifty, an hundred ducats a-piece for his picture<br>in little.<a href='#footnote-45' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>45</sup></a> There is something in this more than natural, if<br>philosophy could find it out.<br>[Flourish of trumpets without.]"},{character:"guildenstern",line:"There are the players."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Gentlemen, you are welcome to Elsinore. Your hands. You are<br>welcome: but my uncle-father and aunt-mother are deceived."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"In what, my dear lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"I am but mad north-north west: when the wind is southerly I<br>know a hawk from a hern-shaw.<a href='#footnote-46' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>46</sup></a><br>[Crosses right]"},{character:"polonius",line:"(Without, left hand) Well be with you, gentlemen!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(Crosses center) Hark you, Guildenstern;&mdash;and Rosencrantz: that great baby you see there is not yet out of his swaddling-clouts."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"(right) Haply he's the second time come to them; for they say an old man is twice a child."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I will prophesy he comes to tell me of the players; mark it.&mdash;You say right, sir: o'Monday morning; 'twas then, indeed.<br>Enter POLONIUS (left hand)"},{character:"polonius",line:"My lord, I have news to tell you."},{character:"hamlet",line:"My lord, I have news to tell you. When Roscius was an actor in Rome,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"polonius",line:"The actors are come hither, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Buz, buz!<a href='#footnote-47' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>47</sup></a>"},{character:"polonius",line:"Upon my honour,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Then came each actor on his ass.<a href='#footnote-48' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>48</sup></a>"},{character:"polonius",line:"The best actors in the world, either for tragedy, comedy,<br>history, pastoral, pastorical-comical, historical-pastoral, scene<br>indivisible, or poem unlimited: Seneca cannot be too heavy, nor<br>Plautus too light.<a href='#footnote-49' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>49</sup></a> For the law of writ and the liberty, these are<br>the only men.<a href='#footnote-50' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>50</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"O, Jephthah, judge of Israel,&mdash;what a treasure hadst thou!"},{character:"polonius",line:"What a treasure had he, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why,&mdash;One fair daughter, and no more,<br>The which he loved passing well."},{character:"polonius",line:"Still harping on my daughter.<br>[Aside.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Am I not i'the right, old Jephthah?"},{character:"polonius",line:"If you call me Jephthah, my lord, I have a daughter that I love passing well."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Nay, that follows not."},{character:"polonius",line:"What follows, then, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why, As by lot, God wot,<a href='#footnote-51' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>51</sup></a> and then, you know, It came to<br>pass, As most like it was,&mdash;The first row of the pious Chanson<a href='#footnote-52' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>52</sup></a><br>will show you more; for look, my abridgment comes.<a href='#footnote-53' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>53</sup></a>"},{character:"stagedirections",line:"Enter Four or Five Players (left hand)&mdash;POLONIUS crosses behind HAMLET to right hand"},{character:"hamlet",line:"You are welcome, masters; welcome, all: O, old friend! Why, thy face<br>is valanced<a href='#footnote-54' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>54</sup></a> since I saw thee last; Com'st thou to beard me<a href='#footnote-55' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>55</sup></a> in<br>Denmark?&mdash;What, my young lady and mistress. By-'r-lady, your ladyship<br>is nearer to heaven than when I saw you last, by the altitude of a<br>chopine.<a href='#footnote-56' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>56</sup></a> You are welcome. We'll e'en to't like French<br>falconers,<a href='#footnote-57' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>57</sup></a> fly at anything we see: We'll have a speech straight:<br>Come, give us a taste of your quality;<a href='#footnote-58' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>58</sup></a> come, a passionate speech."},{character:"1stplayer",line:"(left hand) What speech, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"I heard thee speak me a speech once,&mdash;but it was never acted;<br>or, if it was, not above once; for the play, I remember, pleased not<br>the million; 'twas caviare to the general:<a href='#footnote-59' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>59</sup></a> but it was an<br>excellent play, well digested in the scenes, set down with as much<br>modesty as cunning.<a href='#footnote-60' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>60</sup></a> One speech in it I chiefly loved; 'twas<br>Æneas' tale to Dido; and thereabout of it especially, where he speaks<br>of Priam's slaughter: If it live in your memory, begin at this line;<br>let me see, let me see;&mdash; The rugged Pyrrhus, like the Hyrcanian beast,&mdash;'tis not so: it<br>begins with Pyrrhus:<br>The rugged Pyrrhus,&mdash;he, whose sable arms,<br>Black as his purpose, did the night resemble,<br>Old grandsire Priam seeks."},{character:"polonius",line:"(right) 'Fore Heaven, my lord, well spoken, with good accent and good discretion."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) So proceed you."},{character:"1stplayer",line:"(left) Anon he finds him<br>Striking too short at Greeks; his antique sword,<br>Rebellious to his arm, lies where it falls,<br>Repugnant to command: Unequal match'd,<br>Pyrrhus at Priam drives; in rage strikes wide;<br>But with the whiff and wind of his fell sword<a href='#footnote-61' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>61</sup></a><br>The unnerved father falls.<br>But, as we often see, against some storm,<br>A silence in the heavens, the rack<a href='#footnote-62' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>62</sup></a> stand still,<br>The bold wind speechless, and the orb below<br>As hush as death; anon the dreadful thunder<br>Doth rend the region; So, after Pyrrhus' pause,<br>A roused vengeance sets him new a work;<br>And never did the Cyclops' hammers fall<br>On Mars's armour, forg'd for proof eterne,<br>With less remorse than Pyrrhus' bleeding sword<br>Now falls on Priam.&mdash;<br>Out, out, thou fickle Fortune!"},{character:"polonius",line:"(right) This is too long."},{character:"hamlet",line:"It shall to the barber's, with your beard.&mdash;Say on;&mdash;come to Hecuba."},{character:"1stplayer",line:"But who, ah woe, had seen the mobled queen&mdash;"},{character:"hamlet",line:"The mobled queen?<a href='#footnote-63' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>63</sup></a>"},{character:"polonius",line:"That's good; mobled queen is good."},{character:"1stplayer",line:"Run barefoot up and down, threatening the flames;<br>A clout upon that head<br>Where late the diadem stood; and, for a robe,<br>A blanket, in the alarm of fear caught up;<br>Who this had seen, with tongue in venom steep'd,<br>'Gainst fortune's state would treason have pronounced."},{character:"polonius",line:"Look, whether he has not turned his colour, and has tears in's eyes.&mdash;Prithee, no more."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) 'Tis well; I'll have thee speak out the rest of this<br>soon.&mdash;Good, my lord, will you see the players well bestowed? Do you<br>hear, let them be well used; for they are the abstract and brief<br>chronicles of the time: After your death you were better have a bad<br>epitaph than their ill report while you live."},{character:"polonius",line:"(right) My lord, I will use them according to their desert."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Much better: Use every man after his desert, and who shall<br>'scape whipping? Use them after your own honour and dignity: The less<br>they deserve, the more merit is in your bounty. Take them in.<br>[Crosses to right hand]"},{character:"polonius",line:"Come, sirs."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Follow him, friends: we'll hear a play to-morrow.<br>[Exit POLONIUS with some of the Players, left hand] Old friend<br>[Crosses to center] &mdash;My good friends<br>[To ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN.] I'll leave you till night: you are welcome to Elsinore&mdash;can you play the murder of Gonzago?"},{character:"stagedirections",line:"[Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN, right hand]"},{character:"1stplayer",line:"Ay, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"We'll have it to-morrow night. You could, for a need, study a<br>speech of some dozen or sixteen lines, which I would insert<br>in't&mdash;could you not?"},{character:"1stplayer",line:"Ay, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Very well.&mdash;Follow that lord; and look you mock him not. [Exit Player, left hand] Now I am alone.<br>O, what a rogue and peasant slave am I!<br>Is it not monstrous, that this player here,<br>But in a fiction, in a dream of passion,<br>Could force his soul so to his own conceit,<br>That, from her working, all his visage wann'd;<a href='#footnote-64' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>64</sup></a><br>Tears in his eyes, distraction in's aspect,<br>A broken voice, and his whole function suiting<br>With forms to his conceit?<a href='#footnote-65' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>65</sup></a> And all for nothing!<br>For Hecuba?<br>What's Hecuba to him, or he to Hecuba,<br>That he should weep for her? What would he do,<br>Had he the motive and the cue<a href='#footnote-66' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>66</sup></a> for passion<br>That I have? He would drown the stage with tears,<br>And cleave the general ear with horrid speech;<br>Make mad the guilty, and appal the free;<br>Confound the ignorant, and amaze, indeed,<br>The very faculties of eyes and ears.<br>Yet I,<br>A dull and muddy-mettled rascal, peak,<br>Like John a-dreams,<a href='#footnote-67' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>67</sup></a> unpregnant of my cause,<a href='#footnote-68' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>68</sup></a><br>And can say nothing; no, not for a king,<br>Upon whose property and most dear life<br>A damn'd defeat was made.<a href='#footnote-69' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>69</sup></a> Am I a coward?<br>Who calls me villain? breaks my pate across?<br>Plucks off my beard, and blows it in my face?<br>Tweaks me by the nose? gives me the lie i'the throat,<br>As deep as to the lungs? Who does me this,<br>Ha?<br>Why, I should take it: for it cannot be<br>But I am pigeon-liver'd, and lack gall<br>To make oppression bitter;<a href='#footnote-70' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>70</sup></a> or, ere this,<br>I should have fatted all the region kites<br>With this slave's offal: Bloody, bawdy villain!<br>Remorseless, treacherous, lecherous, kindless<a href='#footnote-71' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>71</sup></a> villain!<br>O, vengeance!<br>Why, what an ass am I! This is most brave,<br>That I, the son of a dear father murder'd,<br>Prompted to my revenge by heaven and hell,<br>Must, like a scold, unpack my heart with words,<br>And fall a cursing, like a very drab,<br>A scullion!<br>Fye upon't! fye! About, my brains!<a href='#footnote-72' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>72</sup></a> I have heard<br>That guilty creatures, sitting at a play,<br>Have by the very cunning of the scene<br>Been struck so to the soul, that presently<br>They have proclaim'd their malefactions;<br>For murder, though it have no tongue, will speak<br>With most miraculous organ. I'll have these players<br>Play something like the murder of my father<br>Before mine uncle: I'll observe his looks;<br>I'll tent him to the quick:<a href='#footnote-73' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>73</sup></a> if he do blench,<a href='#footnote-74' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>74</sup></a><br>I know my course. The spirit that I have seen<br>May be the devil: and the devil hath power<br>To assume a pleasing shape; yea, and, perhaps<br>Out of my weakness and my melancholy<br>(As he is very potent with such spirits),<br>Abuses me to damn me: I'll have good grounds<br>More relative than this:<a href='#footnote-75' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>75</sup></a> The play's the thing<br>Wherein I'll catch the conscience of the king."},{character:"stagedirections",line:"[Exit, right hand]"}]}]},{act:3,scenes:[{scene:1,name:"Scene I",setting:"A room in the castle.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:" Three chairs on left hand, one on right Enter KING and QUEEN, preceded by POLONIUS. OPHELIA, ROSENCRANTZ, and GIULDENSTERN, following (right hand)"},{character:"king",line:"(center) And can you, by no drift of conference,<br>Get from him why he puts on this confusion?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"(right) He does confess he feels himself distracted;<br>But from what cause he will by no means speak."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"(right) Nor do we find him forward<a href='#footnote-1' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>1</sup></a> to be sounded<br>But, with a crafty madness, keeps aloof,<br>When we would bring him on to some confession<br>Of his true state."},{character:"queen",line:"(right center) Did you assay him<a href='#footnote-2' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>2</sup></a><br>To any pastime?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"Madam, it so fell out, that certain players<br>We o'er-raught on the way:<a href='#footnote-3' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>3</sup></a> of these we told him;<br>And there did seem in him a kind of joy<br>To hear of it: They are about the court;<br>And, as I think, they have already order<br>This night to play before him."},{character:"polonius",line:"'Tis most true:<br>And he beseech'd me to entreat your majesties<br>To hear and see the matter."},{character:"king",line:"With all my heart; and it doth much content me<br>To hear him so inclin'd.<br>Good gentlemen, give him a further edge,<br>And drive his purpose on to these delights."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"We shall, my lord. [Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN, right hand]"},{character:"king",line:"Sweet Gertrude, leave us too;<br>For we have closely sent<a href='#footnote-4' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>4</sup></a> for Hamlet hither,<br>That he, as 'twere by accident, may here<br>Affront Ophelia:<a href='#footnote-5' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>5</sup></a><br>Her father and myself (lawful espials<a href='#footnote-6' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>6</sup></a>),<br>Will so bestow ourselves, that, seeing, unseen,<br>We may of their encounter frankly judge;<br>And gather by him, as he is behaved,<br>If't be the affliction of his love or no<br>That thus he suffers for."},{character:"queen",line:"(right) I shall obey you:<br>And for your part, Ophelia, [OPHELIA comes down left hand] I do wish<br>That your good beauties be the happy cause<br>Of Hamlet's wildness: so shall I hope your virtues<br>Will bring him to his wonted way again,<br>To both your honours."},{character:"ophelia",line:"Madam, I wish it may. [Exit QUEEN, right hand]"},{character:"polonius",line:"Ophelia, walk you here. Gracious, so please you,<br>We will bestow ourselves. Read on this book; [To OPHELIA.]<br>That show of such an exercise may colour<br>Your loneliness. We are oft to blame in this,&mdash;<br>'Tis too much prov'd,<a href='#footnote-7' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>7</sup></a> that, with devotion's visage<br>And pious action, we do sugar o'er<br>The devil himself."},{character:"king",line:"O, 'tis too true! how smart<br>A lash that speech doth give my conscience! [Aside.]"},{character:"polonius",line:"I hear him coming: let's withdraw, my lord. [Exeunt KING and POLONIUS, right hand second entrance, and OPHELIA, right hand upper entrance]<br>Enter HAMLET (left hand)"},{character:"hamlet",line:"To be, or not to be, that is the question:<a href='#footnote-8' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>8</sup></a><br>Whether 'tis nobler in the mind to suffer<br>The slings and arrows of outrageous fortune,<br>Or to take arms against a sea of troubles,<a href='#footnote-9' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>9</sup></a><br>And, by opposing end them?&mdash;To die,&mdash;to sleep,<br>No more;&mdash;and by a sleep, to say we end<br>The heart-ache, and the thousand natural shocks<br>That flesh is heir to: 'tis a consummation<br>Devoutly to be wished. To die,&mdash;to sleep,&mdash;<br>To sleep! perchance to dream: ay, there's the rub;<br>For in that sleep of death what dreams may come,<br>When we have shuffled off this mortal coil,<a href='#footnote-10' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>10</sup></a><br>Must give us pause:<a href='#footnote-11' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>11</sup></a> There's the respect<a href='#footnote-12' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>12</sup></a><br>That makes calamity of so long life;<br>For who would bear the whips and scorns of time,<a href='#footnote-13' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>13</sup></a><br>The oppressor's wrong, the proud man's contumely,<a href='#footnote-14' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>14</sup></a><br>The pangs of despised love, the law's delay,<br>The insolence of office, and the spurns<br>That patient merit of the unworthy takes,<br>When he himself might his quietus make<a href='#footnote-15' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>15</sup></a><br>With a bare bodkin?<a href='#footnote-16' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>16</sup></a> Who would fardels bear,<a href='#footnote-17' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>17</sup></a><br>To groan and sweat under a weary life,<br>But that the dread of something after death,<br>The undiscovered country, from whose bourn<a href='#footnote-18' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>18</sup></a><br>No traveller returns,<a href='#footnote-19' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>19</sup></a> puzzles the will,<br>And makes us rather bear those ills we have<br>Than fly to others that we know not of?<br>Thus, conscience does make cowards of us all;<a href='#footnote-20' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>20</sup></a><br>And thus the native hue of resolution<br>Is sicklied o'er with the pale cast of thought;<br>And enterprises of great pith and moment,<a href='#footnote-21' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>21</sup></a><br>With this regard, their currents turn away,<br>And lose the name of action.<a href='#footnote-22' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>22</sup></a>&mdash; [OPHELIA returns.] &mdash;Soft you now!<a href='#footnote-23' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>23</sup></a><br>The fair Ophelia:&mdash;Nymph, in thy orisons<a href='#footnote-24' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>24</sup></a><br>Be all my sins remember'd."},{character:"ophelia",line:"(right center) Good my lord,<br>How does your honour for this many a day?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(left center) I humbly thank you; well."},{character:"ophelia",line:"My lord, I have remembrances of yours,<br>That I have longèd long to re-deliver;<br>I pray you, now receive them."},{character:"hamlet",line:"No, not I;<br>I never gave you aught."},{character:"ophelia",line:"My honour'd lord, you know right well you did;<br>And, with them, words of so sweet breath compos'd<br>As made the things more rich: their perfume lost,<br>Take these again; for to the noble mind<br>Rich gifts wax poor when givers prove unkind.<br>There, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ha, ha! are you honest?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"My lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Are you fair?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"What means your lordship?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"That if you be honest and fair, your honesty should admit no<br>discourse to your beauty.<a href='#footnote-25' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>25</sup></a>"},{character:"ophelia",line:"Could beauty, my lord, have better commerce than with honesty?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ay, truly; for the power of beauty will sooner transform<br>honesty from what it is to a bawd, than the force of honesty can<br>translate beauty into his likeness:<a href='#footnote-26' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>26</sup></a> this was some time a paradox,<br>but now the time gives it proof. I did love you once."},{character:"ophelia",line:"Indeed, my lord, you made me believe so."},{character:"hamlet",line:"You should not have believed me; for virtue cannot so<br>inoculate our old stock, but we shall relish of it:<a href='#footnote-27' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>27</sup></a> I loved you<br>not."},{character:"ophelia",line:"I was the more deceived."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Get thee to a nunnery: Why wouldst thou be a breeder of<br>sinners? I am myself indifferent honest; but yet I could accuse me of<br>such things, that it were better my mother had not borne me: I am<br>very proud, revengeful, ambitious; with more offences at my beck<a href='#footnote-28' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>28</sup></a><br>than I have thoughts to put them in,<a href='#footnote-29' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>29</sup></a> imagination to give them<br>shape, or time to act them in. What should such fellows as I do,<br>crawling between earth and heaven? We are arrant knaves, all;<br>believe none of us. Go thy ways to a nunnery. Where's your father?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"At home, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Let the doors be shut upon him, that he may play the fool<br>nowhere but in's own house. Farewell."},{character:"ophelia",line:"O, help him, you sweet heavens!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"If thou dost marry, I'll give thee this plague for thy dowry.<br>Be thou as chaste as ice, as pure as snow, thou shalt not escape<br>calumny. Get thee to a nunnery; farewell. Or, if thou wilt needs<br>marry, marry a fool; for wise men know well enough what monsters you<br>make of them. To a nunnery, go; go; go."},{character:"ophelia",line:"Heavenly powers, restore him!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"I have heard of your paintings<a href='#footnote-30' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>30</sup></a> too, well enough; Heaven<br>hath given you one face, and you make yourselves another:<a href='#footnote-31' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>31</sup></a> you<br>jig, you amble, and you lisp,<a href='#footnote-32' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>32</sup></a> and nickname Heaven's creatures,<br>and make your wantonness your ignorance.<a href='#footnote-33' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>33</sup></a> Go to, I'll no more<br>of't; it hath made me mad.<br>[HAMLET crosses to right hand] I say, we will have no more marriages: those that are married<br>already, all but one,<a href='#footnote-34' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>34</sup></a> shall live; the rest shall keep as they<br>are. To a nunnery, go. [Exit HAMLET, right hand<a href='#footnote-35' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>35</sup></a>]"},{character:"ophelia",line:"(left) O, what a noble mind is here o'erthrown!<br>The expectancy and rose of the fair state,<a href='#footnote-36' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>36</sup></a><br>The glass of fashion<a href='#footnote-37' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>37</sup></a> and the mould of form,<a href='#footnote-38' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>38</sup></a><br>The observ'd of all observers, quite, quite down!<br>And I, of ladies most deject and wretched,<br>That suck'd the honey of his musick vows,<a href='#footnote-39' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>39</sup></a><br>Now see that noble and most sovereign reason,<br>Like sweet bells jangled, out of tune and harsh:<br>O, woe is me,<br>To have seen what I have seen, see what I see! [Exit OPHELIA, left hand] Re-enter KING and POLONIUS."},{character:"king",line:"Love! his affections do not that way tend;<br>Nor what he spake, though it lack'd form a little,<br>Was not like madness. There's something in his soul,<br>O'er which his melancholy sits on brood;<br>He shall with speed to England,<br>For the demand of our neglected tribute:<br>Haply, the seas, and countries different,<br>With variable objects, shall expel<br>This something-settled matter in his heart;<br>Whereon his brains still beating puts him thus<br>From fashion of himself. What think you on't?"},{character:"polonius",line:"It shall do well: But yet I do believe<br>The origin and commencement of his grief<br>Sprung from neglected love. My lord, do as you please;<br>But, if you hold it fit, after the play,<br>Let his queen mother all alone entreat him<br>To show his grief: let her be round with him;<a href='#footnote-40' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>40</sup></a><br>And I'll be placed, so please you, in the ear<br>Of all their conference. If she find him not,<a href='#footnote-41' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>41</sup></a><br>To England send him; or confine him where<br>Your wisdom best shall think."},{character:"king",line:"It shall be so:<br>Madness in great ones must not unwatch'd go. [Exeunt, left hand] Enter HAMLET and a Player (right hand)"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Speak the speech, I pray you, as I pronounced it to you,<br>trippingly on the tongue: but if you mouth it, as many of our players<br>do, I had as lief<a href='#footnote-42' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>42</sup></a> the town-crier spoke my lines. Nor do not saw<br>the air too much with your hands thus;<a href='#footnote-43' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>43</sup></a> but use all gently: for in<br>the very torrent, tempest, and (as I may say) whirlwind of your<br>passion, you must acquire and beget a temperance that may give it<br>smoothness. O, it offends me to the soul, to hear a robustious<br>perrywig-pated fellow<a href='#footnote-44' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>44</sup></a> tear a passion to tatters, to very rags, to<br>split the ears of the groundlings,<a href='#footnote-45' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>45</sup></a> who, for the most part, are<br>capable of nothing but inexplicable dumb shows and noise: I would<br>have such a fellow whipped for o'erdoing Termagant;<a href='#footnote-46' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>46</sup></a> it<br>out-herods Herod:<a href='#footnote-47' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>47</sup></a> Pray you, avoid it. 1st Play. (right) I warrant your honour."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Be not too tame neither, but let your own discretion be your<br>tutor; suit the action to the word, the word to the action; with this<br>special observance, that you o'erstep not the modesty of nature: for<br>any thing so overdone is from the purpose of playing, whose end, both<br>at the first and now, was and is, to hold, as 'twere, the mirror up<br>to nature; to show virtue her own feature, scorn her own image, and<br>the very age and body of the time its form and pressure.<a href='#footnote-48' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>48</sup></a> Now,<br>this overdone, or come tardy off,<a href='#footnote-49' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>49</sup></a> though it make the unskilful<br>laugh, cannot but make the judicious grieve; the censure of which<br>one<a href='#footnote-50' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>50</sup></a> must, in your allowance,<a href='#footnote-51' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>51</sup></a> o'erweigh a whole theatre of<br>others. O, there be players that I have seen play, and heard others<br>praise, and that highly, not to speak it profanely,<a href='#footnote-52' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>52</sup></a> that, neither<br>having the accent of christians, nor the gait of christian, pagan,<br>nor man, have so strutted and bellowed, that I have thought some of<br>nature's journeymen had made men, and not made them well, they<br>imitated humanity so abominably.<br>[Crosses to right] 1st Play. (left) I hope we have reformed that indifferently<a href='#footnote-53' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>53</sup></a> with us."},{character:"hamlet",line:"O, reform it altogether. And let those that play your clowns<br>speak no more than is set down for them:<a href='#footnote-54' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>54</sup></a> for there be of them<br>that will themselves laugh, to set on some quantity of barren<br>spectators<a href='#footnote-55' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>55</sup></a> to laugh too; though, in the mean time, some necessary<br>question<a href='#footnote-56' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>56</sup></a> of the play be then to be considered: that's villainous,<br>and shows a most pitiful ambition in the fool that uses it. Go, make<br>you ready.<br>[Exit Player, left hand]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"What, ho, Horatio!<br>Enter HORATIO (right hand)"},{character:"horatio",line:"Here, sweet lord, at your service."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Horatio, thou art e'en as just a man<br>As e'er my conversation cop'd withal.<a href='#footnote-57' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>57</sup></a>"},{character:"horatio",line:"O, my dear lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Nay, do not think I flatter;<br>For what advancement may I hope from thee,<br>That no revenue hast, but thy good spirits,<br>To feed and clothe thee? Why should the poor be flatter'd?<br>No, let the candied tongue lick absurd pomp;<br>And crook the pregnant hinges of the knee,<a href='#footnote-58' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>58</sup></a><br>Where thrift may follow fawning. Dost thou hear?<br>Since my dear soul<a href='#footnote-59' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>59</sup></a> was mistress of her choice,<br>And could of men distinguish, her election<br>Hath seal'd thee for herself: for thou hast been<br>As one, in suffering all, that suffers nothing;<br>A man that fortune's buffets and rewards<br>Has ta'en with equal thanks: and bless'd are those<br>Whose blood and judgment<a href='#footnote-60' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>60</sup></a> are so well co-mingled,<br>That they are not a pipe for fortune's finger<br>To sound what stop she please. Give me that man<br>That is not passion's slave, and I will wear him<br>In my heart's core, ay, in my heart of heart,<br>As I do thee.&mdash;Something too much of this.&mdash;<br>There is a play to-night before the king;<br>One scene of it comes near the circumstance<br>Which I have told thee of my father's death:<br>I pr'ythee when thou seest that act a-foot,<br>Even with the very comment of thy soul<a href='#footnote-61' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>61</sup></a><br>Observe my uncle: if his occulted guilt<a href='#footnote-62' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>62</sup></a><br>Do not itself unkennel in one speech,<br>It is a damned ghost that we have seen;<br>And my imaginations are as foul<br>As Vulcan's stithy.<a href='#footnote-63' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>63</sup></a> Give him heedful note:<br>For I mine eyes will rivet to his face;<br>And, after, we will both our judgments join<br>In censure of his seeming.<a href='#footnote-64' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>64</sup></a> [HORATIO goes off, upper entrance left hand]<br>March. Enter KING and QUEEN, preceded by POLONIUS, OPHELIA,<br>HORATIO, ROSENCRANTZ, GUILDENSTERN, Lords, Ladies, and Attendants.<br>KING and QUEEN sit (left hand); OPHELIA (right hand)"},{character:"king",line:"(left) How fares our cousin Hamlet?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Excellent, i'faith; of the cameleon's dish: I eat the<br>air, promise-crammed: you cannot feed capons so."},{character:"king",line:"I have nothing with this answer, Hamlet; these words are not<br>mine.<a href='#footnote-65' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>65</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"No, nor mine, now.<a href='#footnote-66' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>66</sup></a> My lord,&mdash;you played once in the<br>university, you say?<a href='#footnote-67' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>67</sup></a><br>[To POLONIUS, left]"},{character:"polonius",line:"(left center) That did I, my lord; and was accounted a good actor."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) And what did you enact?"},{character:"polonius",line:"I did enact Julius Cæsar:<a href='#footnote-68' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>68</sup></a> I was killed i'the Capitol;<br>Brutus killed me."},{character:"hamlet",line:"It was a brute part of him to kill so capital a calf<br>there.&mdash;Be the players ready?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"Ay, my lord; they stay upon your patience.<a href='#footnote-69' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>69</sup></a>"},{character:"queen",line:"Come hither, my dear Hamlet, sit by me.<br>[Pointing to a chair by her side.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"No, good mother, here's metal more attractive."},{character:"polonius",line:"O, ho! do you mark that?<br>[Aside to the KING.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Lady, shall I lie in your lap?<br>[Lying down at OPHELIA'S feet.]<a href='#footnote-70' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>70</sup></a>"},{character:"ophelia",line:"(right) You are merry, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"O, your only jig-maker.<a href='#footnote-71' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>71</sup></a> What should a man do but be merry?<br>for, look you, how cheerfully my mother looks, and my father died<br>within these two hours."},{character:"ophelia",line:"Nay, 'tis twice two months, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"So long? Nay, then, let the devil wear black, for I'll have a<br>suit of sables.<a href='#footnote-72' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>72</sup></a> O heavens! die two months ago, and not forgotten<br>yet? Then there's hope a great man's memory may outlive his life half<br>a year: But, by'r-lady, he must build churches, then.<a href='#footnote-73' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>73</sup></a>"},{character:"ophelia",line:"What means the play, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Miching mallecho;<a href='#footnote-74' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>74</sup></a> it means mischief."},{character:"ophelia",line:"But what is the argument of the play?<br>Enter a Player as Prologue (left hand) on a raised stage."},{character:"hamlet",line:"We shall know by this fellow.<br>Pro. For us, and for our tragedy,<br>Here stooping to your clemency,<br>We beg your hearing patiently. [Exit, left hand]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Is this a prologue, or the posy of a ring?<a href='#footnote-75' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>75</sup></a>"},{character:"ophelia",line:"'Tis brief, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"As woman's love. Enter a KING and a QUEEN (left hand) on raised stage.<br>P. King. (right) Full thirty times hath Phoebus' cart<a href='#footnote-76' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>76</sup></a> gone round<br>Neptune's salt wash and Tellus' orbèd ground,<a href='#footnote-77' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>77</sup></a><br>Since love our hearts, and Hymen did our hands,<br>Unite commutual in most sacred bands.<br>P. Queen. (left) So many journeys may the sun and moon<br>Make us again count o'er ere love be done!<br>But, woe is me, you are so sick of late,<br>So far from cheer and from your former state,<br>That I distrust you. Yet, though I distrust,<br>Discomfort you, my lord, it nothing must.<br>P. King. 'Faith, I must leave thee, love, and shortly too;<br>My operant powers their functions leave to do:<a href='#footnote-78' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>78</sup></a><br>And thou shalt live in this fair world behind,<br>Honour'd, belov'd; and, haply one as kind<br>For husband shalt thou&mdash;&mdash;<br>P. Queen. O, confound the rest!<br>Such love must needs be treason in my breast:<br>In second husband let me be accurst!<br>None wed the second but who kill'd the first."},{character:"hamlet",line:"That's wormwood.<br>[Aside to HORATIO, right]<br>P. King. I do believe you think what now you speak;<br>But what we do determine oft we break.<a href='#footnote-79' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>79</sup></a><br>So think you thou wilt no second husband wed;<br>But die thy thoughts when thy first lord is dead.<br>P. Queen. Nor earth to me give food, nor heaven light!<br>Sport and repose lock from me day and night!<br>Both here, and hence, pursue me lasting strife,<br>If, once a widow, ever I be wife!<br>P. King. 'Tis deeply sworn."},{character:"hamlet",line:"If she should break it now!&mdash;<br>[To OPHELIA.]<br>P. King. Sweet, leave me here awhile;<br>My spirits grow dull, and fain I would beguile<br>The tedious day with sleep. [Reposes on a bank, right, and sleeps.]<br>P. Queen. Sleep rock thy brain;<br>And never come mischance between us twain! [Exit, left hand]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Madam, how like you this play?"},{character:"queen",line:"The lady doth protest too much, methinks."},{character:"hamlet",line:"O, but she'll keep her word."},{character:"king",line:"Have you heard the argument?<a href='#footnote-80' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>80</sup></a> Is there no offence in't?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"No, no, they do but jest, poison in jest; no offence i'the world."},{character:"king",line:"What do you call the play?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"The mouse-trap.<a href='#footnote-81' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>81</sup></a> Marry, how? Tropically.<a href='#footnote-82' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>82</sup></a> This play is<br>the image of a murder<a href='#footnote-83' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>83</sup></a> done in Vienna: Gonzago is the Duke's name;<br>his wife, Baptista: you shall see anon;&mdash;'tis a knavish piece of<br>work: but what of that? your majesty, and we that have free souls, it<br>touches us not: Let the galled jade wince,<a href='#footnote-84' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>84</sup></a> our withers<a href='#footnote-85' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>85</sup></a> are<br>unwrung.<br>Enter LUCIANUS (left hand) This is one Lucianus, nephew to the king."},{character:"ophelia",line:"You are as good as a chorus,<a href='#footnote-86' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>86</sup></a> my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I could interpret between you and your love, if I could see<br>the puppets dallying.<a href='#footnote-87' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>87</sup></a> Begin, murderer; leave thy damnable faces,<br>and begin. Come:&mdash; &mdash;&mdash;The croaking raven<br>Doth bellow for revenge.<a href='#footnote-88' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>88</sup></a>"},{character:"lucianus",line:" Thoughts black, hands apt, drugs fit, and time agreeing;<br>Confederate season, else no creature seeing;<br>Thou mixture rank, of midnight weeds<a href='#footnote-89' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>89</sup></a> collected,<br>With Hecat's ban thrice blasted, thrice infected,<br>Thy natural magick and dire property,<br>On wholesome life usurp<a href='#footnote-90' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>90</sup></a> immediately. [Pours the poison into the Sleeper's Ears.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"He poisons him i' the garden for his estate. His name's<br>Gonzago: the story is extant, and written in very choice Italian: You<br>shall see anon how the murderer gets the love of Gonzago's wife."},{character:"king",line:"Give me some light: away! All. Lights, lights, lights!<br>[Exeunt all, right and left, but HAMLET and HORATIO.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why, let the strucken deer go weep,<a href='#footnote-91' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>91</sup></a> The hart ungallèd play; For some must watch, while some must sleep: So runs the world away.&mdash; O, good Horatio, I'll take the ghost's word for a thousand pounds.<br>Didst perceive?"},{character:"horatio",line:"(right) Very well, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Upon the talk of the poisoning.&mdash;"},{character:"horatio",line:"I did very well note him."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ah, ah! come, some musick! come, the recorders!"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exit HORATIO, right hand]<br>Enter ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN (left hand) HAMLET seats<br>himself in the chair (right)"},{character:"guildenstern",line:"(left center) Good my lord, vouchsafe me a word with you."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Sir, a whole history."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"The king, sir,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ay, sir, what of him?"},{character:"guildenstern",line:"Is, in his retirement, marvellous distempered.<a href='#footnote-92' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>92</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"With drink, sir?"},{character:"guildenstern",line:"No, my lord, with choler."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Your wisdom should show itself more rich to signify this to<br>the doctor; for, for me to put him to his purgation would perhaps<br>plunge him into more choler."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"Good my lord, put your discourse into some frame, and start<br>not so wildly from my affair."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I am tame, sir:&mdash;pronounce."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"The queen, your mother, in most great affliction of spirit,<br>hath sent me to you."},{character:"hamlet",line:"You are welcome."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"Nay, good my lord, this courtesy is not of the right breed.<br>If it shall please you to make me a wholesome answer, I will do your<br>mother's commandment: if not, your pardon and my return shall be the<br>end of my business."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Sir, I cannot."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"What, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Make you a wholesome answer; my wit's diseased! But, sir, such<br>answer as I can make, you shall command: or rather as you say, my<br>mother: therefore no more, but to the matter: My mother, you say,&mdash;"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"(Crosses to center) Then thus she says: Your behaviour hath<br>struck her into amazement and admiration.<a href='#footnote-93' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>93</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"O wonderful son, that can so astonish a mother! But is there<br>no sequel at the heels of this mother's admiration?&mdash;impart."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"She desires to speak with you in her closet, ere you go to bed."},{character:"hamlet",line:"We shall obey, were she ten times our mother. Have you any<br>further trade with us?<a href='#footnote-94' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>94</sup></a>"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"My lord, you once did love me."},{character:"hamlet",line:"And do still, by these pickers and stealers.<a href='#footnote-95' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>95</sup></a><br>[Rises and comes forward, center]"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"(right) Good my lord, what is your cause of distemper? you do,<br>surely, bar the door of your own liberty, if you deny your griefs to<br>your friend.<a href='#footnote-96' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>96</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Sir, I lack advancement."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"How can that be, when you have the voice of the king himself<br>for your succession in Denmark?<a href='#footnote-97' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>97</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ay, sir, but While the grass grows,&mdash;the proverb is<br>something musty.<a href='#footnote-98' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>98</sup></a><br>Enter HORATIO and Musicians (right hand) O, the recorders:<a href='#footnote-99' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>99</sup></a>&mdash;let me see one.&mdash;So; withdraw with you:&mdash;<br>[Exeunt HORATIO and Musicians right hand GUILDENSTERN,<br>after speaking privately to ROSENCRANTZ, crosses<br>behind HAMLET to right hand] Why do you go about to recover the wind of me,<a href='#footnote-100' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>100</sup></a> as if you would<br>drive me into a toil?<a href='#footnote-101' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>101</sup></a>"},{character:"guildenstern",line:"(right) O, my lord, if my duty be too bold, my love is too<br>unmannerly.<a href='#footnote-102' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>102</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) I do not well understand that. Will you play upon this pipe?"},{character:"guildenstern",line:"My lord, I cannot."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I pray you."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"Believe me, I cannot."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I do beseech you."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"(left) I know no touch of it, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"'Tis as easy as lying: govern these ventages with your fingers<br>and thumb, give it breath with your mouth, and it will discourse most<br>eloquent music.<a href='#footnote-103' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>103</sup></a> Look you, these are the stops."},{character:"guildenstern",line:"But these cannot I command to any utterance of harmony; I<br>have not the skill."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why, look you now, how unworthy a thing you make of me! You<br>would play upon me; you would seem to know my stops; you would pluck<br>out the heart of my mystery; you would sound me from my lowest note<br>to the top of my compass: and there is much music, excellent voice,<br>in this little organ; yet cannot you make it speak. 'Sdeath, do you<br>think I am easier to be played on than a pipe? Call me what<br>instrument you will, though you can fret me, you cannot play upon me.<a href='#footnote-104' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>104</sup></a><br>[Crosses to left hand]<br>Enter POLONIUS (right hand)"},{character:"polonius",line:"(right) My lord, the queen would speak with you, and presently."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Do you see yonder cloud that's almost in shape of a camel?"},{character:"polonius",line:"By the mass, and 'tis like a camel, indeed."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Methinks it is like a weasel."},{character:"polonius",line:"It is backed like a weasel."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Or like a whale?"},{character:"polonius",line:"Very like a whale."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Then will I come to my mother by and by. They fool me to the<br>top of my bent.<a href='#footnote-105' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>105</sup></a> I will come by and by."},{character:"polonius",line:"I will say so."},{character:"hamlet",line:"By and by is easily said.<br>[Exit POLONIUS, right hand Leave me, friends.<br>[Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN, right hand]<br>'Tis now the very witching time of night,<br>When churchyards yawn, and hell itself breathes out<br>Contagion to this world: Now could I drink hot blood,<br>And do such bitter business<a href='#footnote-106' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>106</sup></a> as the day<br>Would quake to look on. Soft! now to my mother.<br>O, heart, lose not thy nature; let not ever<br>The soul of Nero enter this firm bosom:<br>Let me be cruel, not unnatural;<br>I will speak daggers to her, but use none."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exit.]"}]},{scene:2,name:"Scene II",setting:"A room in the same.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter KING, ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN (right hand)"},{character:"king",line:"I like him not; nor stands it safe with us<a href='#footnote-107' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>107</sup></a><br>To let his madness range. Therefore prepare you;<br>I your commission will forthwith despatch,<br>And he to England shall along with you:<br>Arm you, I pray you, to this speedy voyage;<br>For we will fetters put upon this fear,<a href='#footnote-108' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>108</sup></a><br>Which now goes too free-booted."},{character:"rosencrantz, guildenstern",line:"We will haste us."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Cross behind the KING, and exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN, left hand] Enter POLONIUS (right hand)"},{character:"polonius",line:"My lord, he's going to his mother's closet:<br>Behind the arras I'll convey myself,<a href='#footnote-109' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>109</sup></a><br>To hear the process;<a href='#footnote-110' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>110</sup></a> I'll warrant, she'll tax him home:<br>And, as you said, and wisely was it said,<br>'Tis meet that some more audience than a mother,<br>Since nature makes them partial, should o'erhear<br>The speech of vantage.<a href='#footnote-111' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>111</sup></a> Fare you well, my liege: [POLONIUS crosses to left hand]<br>I'll call upon you ere you go to bed,<br>And tell you what I know."},{character:"king",line:"Thanks, dear my lord."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exeunt POLONIUS, left hand, and KING, right hand]"}]},{scene:3,name:"Scene III",setting:"The Queen's chamber.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter QUEEN and POLONIUS (left hand)"},{character:"polonius",line:"He will come straight. Look, you lay home to him:<a href='#footnote-112' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>112</sup></a><br>Tell him his pranks have been too broad<a href='#footnote-113' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>113</sup></a> to bear with,<br>And that your grace hath screen'd and stood between<br>Much heat and him. I'll sconce me even here.<a href='#footnote-114' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>114</sup></a><br>Pray you, be round with him."},{character:"queen",line:"I'll warrant you;<br>Fear me not:&mdash;withdraw, I hear him coming."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[POLONIUS hides himself, left hand upper entrance<br>Enter HAMLET (right)"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(right center) Now, mother, what's the matter?"},{character:"queen",line:"(left center) Hamlet, thou hast thy father much offended."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Mother, you have my father much offended."},{character:"queen",line:"Come, come, you answer with an idle tongue."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Go, go, you question with a wicked tongue."},{character:"queen",line:"Why, how now, Hamlet!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"What's the matter now?"},{character:"queen",line:"Have you forgot me?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"No, by the rood,<a href='#footnote-115' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>115</sup></a> not so:<br>You are the queen, your husband's brother's wife;<br>And&mdash;would it were not so!&mdash;you are my mother."},{character:"queen",line:"Nay, then, I'll set those to you that can speak."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Come, come, and sit you down; you shall not budge;<br>You go not till I set you up a glass<br>Where you may see the inmost part of you."},{character:"queen",line:"What wilt thou do? thou wilt not murder me?<br>Help, help, ho!"},{character:"polonius",line:"(Behind.) What, ho! help!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"How now! a rat?<a href='#footnote-116' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>116</sup></a> [Draws.]<br>Dead, for a ducat, dead! [HAMLET rushes off behind the arras.]"},{character:"polonius",line:"(Behind.) O, I am slain! [Falls and dies.]"},{character:"queen",line:"O me, what hast thou done?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(Returning.) Nay, I know not:<br>Is it the king?"},{character:"queen",line:"O, what a rash and bloody deed is this!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"A bloody deed!&mdash;almost as bad, good mother,<br>As kill a king, and marry with his brother."},{character:"queen",line:"As kill a king!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ay, lady, 'twas my word. [Goes off behind the arras, and returns.]<br>Thou wretched, rash, intruding fool, farewell! [To the dead body of POLONIUS, behind the arras.]<br>I took thee for thy better.<br>Leave wringing of your hands: Peace; sit you down, [To the QUEEN.]<br>And let me wring your heart: for so I shall,<br>If it be made of penetrable stuff;<br>If damnèd custom have not brazed it so,<a href='#footnote-117' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>117</sup></a><br>That it be proof and bulwark against sense.<a href='#footnote-118' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>118</sup></a>"},{character:"queen",line:"(Sits right center)<br>What have I done, that thou dar'st wag thy tongue<br>In noise so rude against me?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(Seated left center) Such an act,<br>That blurs the grace and blush of modesty;<br>Calls virtue, hypocrite; takes off the rose<br>From the fair forehead of an innocent love,<br>And sets a blister there;<a href='#footnote-119' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>119</sup></a> makes marriage vows<br>As false as dicer's oaths: O, such a deed<br>As from the body of contraction plucks<br>The very soul;<a href='#footnote-120' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>120</sup></a> and sweet religion makes<br>A rhapsody of words.&mdash;<br>Ah, me, that act!"},{character:"queen",line:"Ah me, what act?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Look here, upon this picture, and on this,<br>The counterfeit presentment<a href='#footnote-121' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>121</sup></a> of two brothers.<br>See, what a grace was seated on this brow;<br>Hypérion's curls;<a href='#footnote-122' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>122</sup></a> the front of Jove himself;<br>An eye like Mars, to threaten and command;<br>A station like the herald Mercury<a href='#footnote-123' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>123</sup></a><br>New-lighted on a heaven-kissing hill;<br>A combination, and a form, indeed,<br>Where every god did seem to set his seal,<br>To give the world assurance of a man;<br>This was your husband.&mdash;Look you now, what follows:<br>Here is your husband; like a mildew'd ear,<br>Blasting his wholesome brother.<a href='#footnote-124' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>124</sup></a> Have you eyes?<br>Could you on this fair mountain leave to feed,<br>And batten on this moor?<a href='#footnote-125' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>125</sup></a> Ha! have you eyes?<br>You cannot call it love; for, at your age<br>The hey-day in the blood<a href='#footnote-126' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>126</sup></a> is tame, it's humble,<br>And waits upon the judgment: And what judgment<br>Would step from this to this?<br>O shame! where is thy blush? Rebellious hell,<br>If thou canst mutine,<a href='#footnote-127' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>127</sup></a> in a matron's bones,<br>To flaming youth let virtue be as wax,<br>And melt in her own fire."},{character:"queen",line:"O, Hamlet, speak no more:<br>Thou turn'st mine eyes into my very soul;<br>And there I see such black and grainèd spots<br>As will not leave their tinct.<a href='#footnote-128' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>128</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Nay, but to live<br>In the rank sweat of an enseamed bed,&mdash;&mdash;<a href='#footnote-129' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>129</sup></a>"},{character:"queen",line:"O, speak to me no more;<br>No more, sweet Hamlet!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"A murderer and a villain:<br>A slave that is not twentieth part the tythe<br>Of your precedent lord;&mdash;a vice of kings;<a href='#footnote-130' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>130</sup></a><br>A cutpurse of the empire and the rule;<br>That from a shelf the precious diadem stole,<br>And put it in his pocket!<a href='#footnote-131' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>131</sup></a>"},{character:"queen",line:"No more!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"A king<br>Of shreds and patches.<a href='#footnote-132' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>132</sup></a> [Enter Ghost, right]<br>Save me [Starts from his chair],<br>and hover o'er me with your wings,<br>You heavenly guards! What would your gracious figure?"},{character:"queen",line:"Alas, he's mad! [Rising.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(left) Do you not come your tardy son to chide,<br>That, laps'd in time and passion,<a href='#footnote-133' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>133</sup></a> lets go by<br>The important acting of your dread command?<br>O, say!"},{character:"ghost",line:"(right) Do not forget: This visitation<br>Is but to whet thy almost blunted purpose.<br>But, look, amazement on thy mother sits:<br>O, step between her and her fighting soul.<br>Speak to her Hamlet."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How is it with you, lady?"},{character:"queen",line:"Alas, how is't with you,<br>That you do bend your eye on vacancy,<br>And with the incorporal air do hold discourse?<br>Forth at your eyes your spirits wildly peep.<br>O gentle son, [Crosses to HAMLET.]<br>Upon the heat and flame of thy distemper<br>Sprinkle cool patience.<a href='#footnote-134' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>134</sup></a> Whereon do you look?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"On him, on him!&mdash;Look you, how pale he glares!<br>His form and cause conjoin'd, preaching to stones,<br>Would make them capable.<a href='#footnote-135' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>135</sup></a> Do not look upon me;<br>Lest with this piteous action, you convert<br>My stern effects:<a href='#footnote-136' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>136</sup></a> then what I have to do<br>Will want true colour; tears perchance, for blood."},{character:"queen",line:"To whom do you speak this?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Do you see nothing there?"},{character:"queen",line:"Nothing at all; yet all that is, I see.<a href='#footnote-137' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>137</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Nor did you nothing hear?"},{character:"queen",line:"No, nothing but ourselves."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why, look you there! look, how it steals away! [Ghost crosses to left]<br>My father in his habit as he lived!<a href='#footnote-138' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>138</sup></a><br>Look, where he goes, even now, out at the portal! [Exit Ghost, left hand HAMLET sinks into chair center The QUEEN falls on her knees by his side.]"},{character:"queen",line:"This is the very coinage of your brain:<br>This bodiless creation ecstasy<br>Is very cunning in.<a href='#footnote-139' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>139</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ecstasy!<br>My pulse, as yours, doth temperately keep time,<br>And makes as healthful music: It is not madness<br>That I have uttered: bring me to the test,<br>And I the matter will re-word; which madness<br>Would gambol from.<a href='#footnote-140' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>140</sup></a> Mother, for love of grace, Rising.]<br>Lay not that flattering unction to your soul,<br>That not your trespass, but my madness speaks:<br>It will but skin and film<a href='#footnote-141' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>141</sup></a> the ulcerous place,<br>Whiles rank corruption, mining all within,<br>Infects unseen. Confess yourself to heaven;<br>Repent what's past; avoid what is to come."},{character:"queen",line:"O, Hamlet! thou hast cleft my heart in twain."},{character:"hamlet",line:"O, throw away the worser part of it,<br>And live the purer with the other half.<br>Good night: but go not to my uncle's bed; [Raising the QUEEN.]<br>Assume a virtue, if you have it not.<br>Once more, good night!<br>And when you are desirous to be bless'd,<br>I'll blessing beg of you.<a href='#footnote-142' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>142</sup></a> For this same lord, [Pointing to POLONIUS.]<br>I do repent:<br>I will bestow him, and will answer well<br>The death I gave him. So, again, good night. [Exit QUEEN, right hand]<br>I must be cruel, only to be kind:<br>Thus bad begins, and worse remains behind."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exit HAMLET behind the arras, left hand upper entrance]"}]}]},{act:4,scenes:[{scene:1,name:"Scene I",setting:"A room in the castle.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter KING and QUEEN, from (right hand) centre."},{character:"king",line:"There's matter in these sighs, these profound heaves:<br>You must translate:<a href='#footnote-1' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>1</sup></a> 'tis fit we understand them.<br>How does Hamlet?"},{character:"queen",line:"Mad as the sea and wind, when both contend<br>Which is the mightier: In his lawless fit,<br>Behind the arras hearing something stir,<br>Whips out his rapier, cries A rat, a rat!<br>And, in this brainish apprehension,<a href='#footnote-2' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>2</sup></a> kills<br>The unseen good old man."},{character:"king",line:"O heavy deed!<br>It had been so with us, had we been there:<br>Where is he gone?"},{character:"queen",line:"To draw apart the body he hath kill'd."},{character:"king",line:"The sun no sooner shall the mountains touch,<br>But we will ship him hence: and this vile deed<br>We must, with all our majesty and skill,<br>Both countenance and excuse.&mdash;Ho, Guildenstern! Enter ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN (left hand)<br>Friends both, go join you with some further aid:<br>Hamlet in madness hath Polonius slain,<br>And from his mother's closet hath he dragg'd him:<br>Go seek him out; speak fair, and bring the body<br>Into the chapel. [ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN cross to right]<br>I pray you, haste in this. [Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and GUILDENSTERN, right hand]<br>Go, Gertrude, we'll call up our wisest friends;<br>And let them know, both what we mean to do,<br>And what's untimely done. [Exit QUEEN, right center]<br>How dangerous is it that this man goes loose!<br>Yet must not we put the strong law on him:<br>He's lov'd of the distracted multitude,<br>Who like not in their judgment, but their eyes;<br>And where 'tis so, the offender's scourge is weigh'd,<br>But never the offence.<a href='#footnote-3' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>3</sup></a> [Enter ROSENCRANTZ] (right)<br>How now! what hath befallen?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"Where the dead body is bestowed, my lord,<br>We cannot get from him."},{character:"king",line:"But where is he?"},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"Without, my lord; guarded, to know your pleasure."},{character:"king",line:"Bring him before us."},{character:"rosencrantz",line:"Ho, Guildenstern! bring in my lord."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Enter HAMLET, GUILDENSTERN, and Attendants (right hand)]"},{character:"king",line:"(center) Now, Hamlet, where's Polonius?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(right) At supper."},{character:"king",line:"At supper? Where?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Not where he eats, but where he is eaten: a<br>certain convocation of politick worms<a href='#footnote-4' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>4</sup></a> are e'en at him."},{character:"king",line:"Where's Polonius?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"In Heaven; send thither to see: if your messenger<br>find him not there, seek him i'the other place<br>yourself. But, indeed, if you find him not within this<br>month, you shall nose him as you go up the stairs into<br>the lobby."},{character:"king",line:"Go seek him there. [To GUILDENSTERN.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"He will stay till you come. [Exit GUILDENSTERN, right hand]"},{character:"king",line:"Hamlet, this deed, for thine especial safety,<br>Must send thee hence:<br>Therefore prepare thyself;<br>The bark is ready, and the wind at help,<a href='#footnote-5' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>5</sup></a><br>For England."},{character:"hamlet",line:"For England!"},{character:"king",line:"Ay, Hamlet."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Good."},{character:"king",line:"So is it, if thou knew'st our purposes."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I see a cherub that sees them. But, come; for<br>England!&mdash;Farewell, dear mother."},{character:"king",line:"Thy loving father, Hamlet."},{character:"hamlet",line:"My mother: Father and mother is man and wife; man and wife is<br>one flesh; and so, my mother. Come, for England. [Exit, right hand]"},{character:"king",line:"Follow him at foot; tempt him with speed aboard;<br>Away! for everything is seal'd and done. [Exeunt ROSENCRANTZ and Attendants, right hand]<br>And, England, if my love thou hold'st at aught,<br>Thou may'st not coldly set<a href='#footnote-6' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>6</sup></a><br>Our sovereign process;<a href='#footnote-7' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>7</sup></a> which imports at full,<br>By letters conjuring to that effect,<a href='#footnote-8' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>8</sup></a><br>The present death of Hamlet. Do it, England;<br>For thou must cure me: 'Till I know 'tis done,<br>Howe'er my haps,<a href='#footnote-9' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>9</sup></a> my joys will ne'er begin. [Exit KING, left hand] Enter QUEEN and HORATIO (right centre.)"},{character:"queen",line:"&mdash;&mdash;I will not speak with her."},{character:"horatio",line:"She is importunate; indeed, distract:<br>'Twere good she were spoken with; for she may strew<br>Dangerous conjectures in ill-breeding minds."},{character:"queen",line:"Let her come in. [Exit HORATIO, right center] Re-enter HORATIO, with OPHELIA (right centre.)"},{character:"ophelia",line:"Where is the beauteous majesty of Denmark?"},{character:"queen",line:"How now, Ophelia!"},{character:"ophelia",line:"(center) [Singing.] How should I your true love know From another one? By his cockle hat and staff, And his sandal shoon.<a href='#footnote-10' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>10</sup></a>"},{character:"queen",line:"(left center) Alas, sweet lady, what imports this song?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"Say you? nay, pray you, mark. [Sings.] He is dead and gone, lady, He is dead and gone; At his head a grass-green turf, At his heels a stone."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter the KING (left hand)"},{character:"queen",line:"Nay, but, Ophelia,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"ophelia",line:"Pray you, mark. [Sings.] White his shroud as the mountain-snow, Larded all with sweet flowers;<a href='#footnote-11' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>11</sup></a> Which bewept to the grave did go With true-love showers."},{character:"king",line:"How do you, pretty lady?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"Well, Heaven 'ield you!<a href='#footnote-12' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>12</sup></a> (Crosses to the KING.)<br>They say the owl was a baker's daughter.<a href='#footnote-13' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>13</sup></a> We know<br>what we are, but know not what we may be."},{character:"king",line:"Conceit upon her father.<a href='#footnote-14' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>14</sup></a>"},{character:"ophelia",line:"Pray, you, let us have no words of this; but when<br>they ask you what it means, say you this: To-morrow is Saint Valentine's day, All in the morning betime, And I, a maid at your window, To be your Valentine:"},{character:"king",line:"Pretty Ophelia!"},{character:"ophelia",line:"Indeed, without an oath, I'll make an end on't: Then up he rose, and don'd his clothes, And dupp'd<a href='#footnote-15' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>15</sup></a> the chamber door; Let in the maid, that out a maid Never departed more. [Crosses to right hand]"},{character:"king",line:"(left) How long hath she been thus?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"(right) I hope all will be well. We must be patient: but I cannot<br>choose but weep, to think they should lay him i'the cold ground. My<br>brother shall know of it; and so I thank you for your good counsel.<br>Come, my coach! Good night, ladies; good night, sweet ladies; good<br>night, good night. [Exit, right center]"},{character:"king",line:"Follow her close; give her good watch, I pray you. [Exit HORATIO, through centre right]<br>O! this is the poison of deep grief; it springs<br>All from her father's death.<br>O, Gertrude, Gertrude,<br>When sorrows come, they come not single spies,<br>But in battalions! Enter MARCELLUS (right centre.)"},{character:"king",line:"What is the matter?"},{character:"marcellus",line:"Save yourself, my lord:<br>The young Laertes, in a riotous head,<a href='#footnote-16' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>16</sup></a><br>O'erbears your officers. The rabble call him lord;<br>They cry, Choose we: Laertes shall be king!<br>Caps, hands, and tongues, applaud it to the clouds,<br>Laertes shall be king, Laertes king!"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Noise within, right center] Enter LAERTES, armed; Danes following (right center)"},{character:"laertes",line:"Where is this king?&mdash;Sirs, stand you all without."},{character:"danes",line:"No, let's come in."},{character:"laertes",line:"I pray you, give me leave."},{character:"danes",line:"We will, we will. [They retire without, right hand]"},{character:"laertes",line:"O, thou vile king,<br>Give me my father.<br>Queen (Interposing.)<br>Calmly, good Laertes."},{character:"laertes",line:"(right) That drop of blood that's calm proclaims me bastard;<br>Cries cuckold to my father; brands the harlot<br>Even here, between the chaste unsmirched brow<br>Of my true mother.<a href='#footnote-17' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>17</sup></a>"},{character:"king",line:"(left) What is the cause, Laertes,<br>That thy rebellion looks so giant-like?<br>Let him go, Gertrude; do not fear our person:<br>There's such divinity doth hedge a king,<a href='#footnote-18' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>18</sup></a><br>That treason can but peep to what it would,<br>Acts little of his will.<br>Let him go, Gertrude. [QUEEN obeys.]"},{character:"laertes",line:"Where is my father?"},{character:"king",line:"Dead."},{character:"queen",line:"But not by him."},{character:"king",line:"Let him demand his fill."},{character:"laertes",line:"How came he dead? I'll not be juggled with:<br>To hell, allegiance! To this point I stand,<br>That both the worlds I give to negligence,<a href='#footnote-19' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>19</sup></a><br>Let come what comes; only I'll be reveng'd<br>Most throughly for my father."},{character:"king",line:"Who shall stay you!"},{character:"laertes",line:"My will, not all the world's:<a href='#footnote-20' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>20</sup></a><br>And, for my means, I'll husband them so well,<br>They shall go far with little."},{character:"king",line:"Good Laertes,<br>That I am guiltless of your father's death,<br>And am most sensible in grief<a href='#footnote-21' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>21</sup></a> for it,<br>It shall as level to your judgment 'pear<br>As day does to your eye."},{character:"horatio",line:"(Without.)<br>Oh, poor Ophelia!"},{character:"king",line:"Let her come in. Enter OPHELIA (right center), fantastically dressed with Straws and Flowers."},{character:"laertes",line:"(Goes up left center) O rose of May!<br>Dear maid, kind sister, sweet Ophelia!<br>O heavens! is't possible, a young maid's wits<br>Should be as mortal as an old man's life?"},{character:"ophelia",line:"(right center) They bore him barefac'd on the bier; And on his grave rain many a tear,&mdash;<br>Fare you well, my dove!"},{character:"laertes",line:"(Coming down right)<br>Hadst thou thy wits, and didst persuade revenge,<br>It could not move thus."},{character:"ophelia",line:"You must sing, Down-a-down,<a href='#footnote-22' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>22</sup></a> an you call him a-down-a. O,<br>how well the wheel becomes it!<a href='#footnote-23' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>23</sup></a> It is the false steward, that<br>stole his master's daughter."},{character:"laertes",line:"This nothing's more than matter."},{character:"ophelia",line:"There's rosemary, that's for remembrance;<a href='#footnote-24' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>24</sup></a> pray you, love,<br>remember: and there is pansies,<a href='#footnote-25' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>25</sup></a> that's for thoughts."},{character:"laertes",line:"A document in madness; thoughts and remembrance fitted."},{character:"ophelia",line:"There's fennel for you,<br>(crosses to the KING on left hand) and columbines:<a href='#footnote-26' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>26</sup></a> there's rue for you;<br>(turns to the QUEEN, who is right center) and here's some for me:&mdash;we may call it herb of grace<br>o'Sundays:<a href='#footnote-27' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>27</sup></a>&mdash;you may wear your rue with a difference.<a href='#footnote-28' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>28</sup></a>&mdash;There's<br>a daisy:<a href='#footnote-29' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>29</sup></a>&mdash;I would give you some violets,<a href='#footnote-30' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>30</sup></a> but they withered<br>all when my father died:&mdash;They say he made a good end,&mdash;&mdash;<br>For bonny sweet Robin is all my joy&mdash;<a href='#footnote-31' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>31</sup></a>"},{character:"laertes",line:"(right) Thought and affliction,<a href='#footnote-32' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>32</sup></a> passion, hell itself,<br>She turns to favour and to prettiness."},{character:"ophelia",line:"And will he not come again? And will he not come again? No, no, he is dead, Gone to his death-bed, He never will come again. His beard was white as snow, All flaxen was his poll: He is gone, he is gone, And we cast away moan: Heaven 'a mercy on his soul!<br>And of all christian souls, I pray Heaven. Heaven be wi' you. [Exit OPHELIA, right center, QUEEN following.]"},{character:"laertes",line:"Do you see this, O Heaven?"},{character:"king",line:"(left center) Laertes, I must commune with your grief,<a href='#footnote-33' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>33</sup></a><br>Or you deny me right.<br>Be you content to lend your patience to us,<br>And we shall jointly labour with your soul<br>To give it due content."},{character:"laertes",line:"(right center) Let this be so;<br>His means of death, his obscure funeral,&mdash;<br>No trophy, sword, nor hatchment o'er his bones,<a href='#footnote-34' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>34</sup></a><br>No noble rite nor formal ostentation,&mdash;<br>Cry to be heard,<a href='#footnote-35' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>35</sup></a> as 'twere from heaven to earth,<br>That I must call't in question."},{character:"king",line:"So you shall;<br>And where the offence is let the great axe fall.<a href='#footnote-36' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>36</sup></a><br>How now! what news?"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter BERNARDO (right handcenter)"},{character:"bernardo",line:"(center) Letters, my lord, from Hamlet:<br>This to your majesty; this to the Queen."},{character:"king",line:"From Hamlet! who brought them?"},{character:"bernardo",line:"Sailors, my lord, they say; I saw them not."},{character:"king",line:"Laertes, you shall hear them.&mdash;<br>Leave us. [Exit, left handcenter] [Reads.] High and mighty, You shall know I am set naked on your kingdom.<a href='#footnote-37' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>37</sup></a><br>To morrow shall I beg leave to see your kingly eyes: when I shall,<br>first asking your pardon thereunto, recount the occasion of my sudden<br>and more strange return. HAMLET.<br>What should this mean? Are all the rest come back?<br>Or is it some abuse, and no such thing?"},{character:"laertes",line:"(right) Know you the hand?"},{character:"king",line:"(left) 'Tis Hamlet's character:<a href='#footnote-38' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>38</sup></a> Naked,&mdash;<br>And in a postscript here, he says, alone.<br>Can you advise me?"},{character:"laertes",line:"I am lost in it, my lord. But let him come;<br>It warms the very sickness in my heart,<br>That I shall live and tell him to his teeth,<br>Thus diddest thou."},{character:"king",line:"If it be so, Laertes,<br>Will you be rul'd by me?"},{character:"laertes",line:"Ay, my lord;<br>So you will not o'er-rule me to a peace."},{character:"king",line:"To thine own peace.<br>Some two months since,<br>Here was a gentleman of Normandy,<br>He made confession of<a href='#footnote-39' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>39</sup></a> you;<br>And gave you such a masterly report,<br>For art and exercise in your defence,<a href='#footnote-40' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>40</sup></a><br>And for your rapier most especially,<br>That he cried out, 'twould be a sight indeed,<br>If one could match you: this report of his<br>Did Hamlet so envenom with his envy,<br>That he could nothing do but wish and beg<br>Your sudden coming o'er, to play with you.<br>Now, out of this,&mdash;&mdash;"},{character:"laertes",line:"What out of this, my lord?"},{character:"king",line:"Laertes, was your father dear to you?<br>Or are you like the painting of a sorrow,<br>A face without a heart?"},{character:"laertes",line:"Why ask you this?"},{character:"king",line:"Hamlet return'd shall know you are come home:<br>We'll put on those shall praise your excellence,<br>And set a double varnish on the fame<br>The Frenchman gave you; bring you, in fine, together,<br>And wager o'er your heads; he, being remiss,<a href='#footnote-41' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>41</sup></a><br>Most generous, and free from all contriving,<br>Will not peruse the foils:<a href='#footnote-42' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>42</sup></a> so that, with ease,<br>Or with a little shuffling, you may choose<br>A sword unbated,<a href='#footnote-43' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>43</sup></a> and, in a pass of practice,<a href='#footnote-44' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>44</sup></a><br>Requite him for your father."},{character:"laertes",line:"I will do't:<br>And, for the purpose, I'll anoint my sword.<br>I bought an unction of a mountebank,<br>So mortal, that but dip a knife in it,<br>Where it draws blood no cataplasm<a href='#footnote-45' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>45</sup></a> so rare,<br>Collected from all simples<a href='#footnote-46' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>46</sup></a> that have virtue<br>Under the moon, can save the thing from death<br>That is but scratch'd withal: I'll touch my point<br>With this contagion, that, if I gall him slightly,<br>It may be death."},{character:"king",line:"(left) Let's further think of this;<br>We'll make a solemn wager on your cunnings,<a href='#footnote-47' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>47</sup></a><br>When in your motion<a href='#footnote-48' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>48</sup></a> you are hot and dry,<br>(As make your bouts more violent to that end,)<br>And that he calls for drink, I'll have prepared him<br>A chalice for the nonce;<a href='#footnote-49' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>49</sup></a> whereon but sipping,<br>If he by chance escape your venom'd stuck,<a href='#footnote-50' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>50</sup></a><br>Our purpose may hold there. But stay, what noise? [Enter QUEEN (right center)]"},{character:"queen",line:"(center) One woe doth tread upon another's heel,<br>So fast they follow: Your sister's drown'd, Laertes."},{character:"laertes",line:"(right) Drown'd! O, where?"},{character:"queen",line:"There is a willow grows aslant a brook,<br>That shows his hoar leaves in the glassy stream;<br>Therewith fantastick garlands did she make<br>Of crow-flowers, nettles, daisies, and long purples;<a href='#footnote-51' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>51</sup></a><br>There, on the pendent boughs her cornet weeds<br>Clambering to hang, an envious sliver broke;<br>When down her weedy trophies, and herself,<br>Fell in the weeping brook."},{character:"laertes",line:"I forbid my tears: But yet<br>It is our trick:<a href='#footnote-52' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>52</sup></a> nature her custom holds,<br>Let shame say what it will: when these are gone,<br>The woman will be out.<a href='#footnote-53' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>53</sup></a><br>Adieu, my lord:<br>I have a speech of fire, that fain would blaze,<br>But that this folly drowns it.<a href='#footnote-54' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>54</sup></a>"},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exeunt. center]"}]}]},{act:5,scenes:[{scene:1,name:"Scene I",setting:"A church yard.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter two Clowns,<a href='#footnote-1' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>1</sup></a> with spades, &c. (left hand upper entrance)"},{character:"first clown",line:"(right) Is she to be buried in christian burial that wilfully<br>seeks her own salvation?"},{character:"second clown",line:"(left) I tell thee she is; therefore make her grave<br>straight:<a href='#footnote-2' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>2</sup></a> the crowner<a href='#footnote-3' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>3</sup></a> hath set on her, and finds it christian burial."},{character:"first clown",line:"How can that be, unless she drowned herself in her own<br>defence?"},{character:"second clown",line:"Why, 'tis found so."},{character:"first clown",line:"It must be se offendendo;<a href='#footnote-4' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>4</sup></a> it cannot be else. For here<br>lies the point: If I drown myself wittingly, it argues an act: and an<br>act hath three branches; it is, to act, to do, and to perform:<a href='#footnote-5' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>5</sup></a><br>argal,<a href='#footnote-6' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>6</sup></a> she drowned herself wittingly."},{character:"second clown",line:"Nay, but hear you, goodman delver.<a href='#footnote-7' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>7</sup></a>"},{character:"first clown",line:"Give me leave. Here lies the water; good: here stands the<br>man; good: If the man go to this water, and drown himself, it is,<br>will he, nill he, he goes,<a href='#footnote-8' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>8</sup></a> mark you that; but if the water come<br>to him and drown him, he drowns not himself: argal, he that is not<br>guilty of his own death shortens not his own life."},{character:"second clown",line:"But is this law?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Ay, marry is't; crowner's-quest law.<a href='#footnote-9' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>9</sup></a>"},{character:"second clown",line:"Will you ha' the truth on't? If this had not been a<br>gentlewoman, she should have been buried out of christian burial."},{character:"first clown",line:"Why, there thou say'st:<a href='#footnote-10' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>10</sup></a> And the more pity that great<br>folks should have countenance in this world to drown or hang<br>themselves, more than their even christian.<a href='#footnote-11' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>11</sup></a> Come, my spade. There<br>is no ancient gentlemen but gardeners, ditchers, and grave-makers:<br>they hold up Adam's profession."},{character:"second clown",line:"Was he a gentleman?<a href='#footnote-12' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>12</sup></a>"},{character:"first clown",line:"He was the first that ever bore arms. I'll put another<br>question to thee: if thou answerest me not to the purpose, confess thyself&mdash;&mdash;<a href='#footnote-13' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>13</sup></a>"},{character:"second clown",line:"Go to."},{character:"first clown",line:"What is he that builds stronger than either the mason, the<br>shipwright, or the carpenter?"},{character:"second clown",line:"The gallows-maker; for that frame outlives a thousand tenants."},{character:"first clown",line:"I like thy wit well, in good faith: the gallows does well;<br>But how does it well? it does well to those that do ill: now, thou<br>dost ill to say the gallows is built stronger than the church: argal,<br>the gallows may do well to thee. To't again, come."},{character:"second clown",line:"Who builds stronger than a mason, a shipwright, or a carpenter?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Ay, tell me that, and unyoke.<a href='#footnote-14' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>14</sup></a>"},{character:"second clown",line:"Marry, now I can tell."},{character:"first clown",line:"To't."},{character:"second clown",line:"Mass, I cannot tell."},{character:"first clown",line:"Cudgel thy brains no more about it,<a href='#footnote-15' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>15</sup></a> for your dull ass<br>will not mend his pace with beating; and, when you are asked this<br>question next, say, a grave-maker, the houses that he makes, last<br>till doomsday. Go, get thee to Yaughan, and fetch me a stoup of<br>liquor.<a href='#footnote-16' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>16</sup></a><br>[Exit 2nd Clown, left hand upper entrance]<br>Enter HAMLET and HORATIO (left hand upper entrance)<br>First Clown digs and sings. In youth, when I did love, did love,<a href='#footnote-17' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>17</sup></a> Methought, it was very sweet, To contract, O, the time, for, ah, my behove O, methought, there was nothing meet."},{character:"hamlet",line:" (Behind the grave.) Has this fellow no feeling of his business, he sings at grave-making?"},{character:"horatio",line:" (On HAMLET'S right) Custom hath made it in him a property of easiness."},{character:"hamlet",line:"'Tis e'en so: the hand of little employment hath the daintier sense.<a href='#footnote-18' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>18</sup></a>"},{character:"first clown",line:" But age, with his stealing steps, Hath clawed me in his clutch,<br>And hath shipped me into the land, As if I had never been such.<br>[Throws up a skull.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"That skull had a tongue in it, and could sing once: How the<br>knave jowls it to the ground, as if it were Cain's jaw-bone, that did<br>the first murder! This might be the pate of a politician, which this<br>ass now o'er-reaches; one that would circumvent Heaven, might it not?"},{character:"horatio",line:"It might, my lord.<br>[Gravedigger throws up bones.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Did these bones cost no more the breeding, but to play at<br>loggats with them?<a href='#footnote-19' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>19</sup></a> mine ache to think on't."},{character:"first clown",line:" [Sings.]<br>A pick-axe and a spade, a spade, For and a shrouding sheet:<a href='#footnote-20' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>20</sup></a><br>O, a pit of clay for to be made For such a guest is meet.<br>[Throws up a skull.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"There's another: Why may not that be the skull of a lawyer?<br>Where be his quiddits now, his quillets,<a href='#footnote-21' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>21</sup></a> his cases, his tenures,<br>and his tricks? Why does he suffer this rude knave now to knock him<br>about the sconce<a href='#footnote-22' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>22</sup></a> with a dirty shovel, and will not tell him of<br>his action of battery? I will speak to this fellow.&mdash;Whose grave's this, sirrah?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Mine, sir.&mdash;<br>[Sings.]<br>O, a pit of clay for to be made For such a guest is meet."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(right of grave.) I think it be thine, indeed; for thou liest<br>in't."},{character:"first clown",line:"You lie out on't, sir, and therefore it is not yours: for<br>my part, I do not lie in't, yet it is mine."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Thou dost lie in't, to be in't, and say it is thine: 'tis for<br>the dead, not for the quick; therefore thou liest. 1st. Clo. 'Tis a quick lie, sir; 'twill away again, from me to you."},{character:"hamlet",line:"What man dost thou dig it for?"},{character:"first clown",line:"For no man, sir."},{character:"hamlet",line:"What woman, then?"},{character:"first clown",line:"For none, neither."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Who is to be buried in't?"},{character:"first clown",line:"One that was a woman, sir; but, rest her soul, she's dead."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How absolute the knave is!<a href='#footnote-23' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>23</sup></a> we must speak by the card,<a href='#footnote-24' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>24</sup></a><br>or equivocation will undo us,<br>[To HORATIO, right] How long hast thou been a grave-maker?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Of all the days i'the year, I came to't that day that our<br>last king Hamlet overcame Fortinbras."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How long's that since?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Cannot you tell that? every fool can tell that: It was the<br>very day that young Hamlet was born,<a href='#footnote-25' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>25</sup></a> he that is mad, and sent<br>into England."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Ay, marry, why was he sent into England?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Why, because he was mad: he shall recover his wits there;<br>or, if he do not, 'tis no great matter there."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why?"},{character:"first clown",line:"'Twill not be seen in him there; there the men are as mad as he."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How came he mad?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Very strangely, they say."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How strangely?"},{character:"first clown",line:"'Faith, e'en with losing his wits."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Upon what ground?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Why, here in Denmark: I have been sexton here, man and<br>boy, thirty years."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How long will a man lie i'the earth ere he rot?"},{character:"first clown",line:"'Faith, if he be not rotten before he die, he will last<br>you some eight year or nine year: a tanner will last you nine year."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Why he more than another?"},{character:"first clown",line:"Why, sir, his hide is so tanned with his trade, that he<br>will keep out water a great while; and your water is a sore decayer<br>of your ill-begotten dead body. Here's a skull now, hath lain in the<br>earth three-and-twenty years."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Whose was it?"},{character:"first clown",line:"O, a mad fellow's it was: Whose do you think it was?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Nay, I know not."},{character:"first clown",line:"A pestilence on him for a mad rogue! he poured a flagon of<br>Rhenish on my head once. This same skull, sir, was Yorick's skull,<br>the king's jester."},{character:"hamlet",line:"This?<br>[Takes the skull.]"},{character:"first clown",line:"E'en that."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Alas, poor Yorick! I knew him, Horatio: a fellow of infinite<br>jest, of most excellent fancy: he hath borne me on his back a<br>thousand times. Here hung those lips that I have kissed I know not<br>how oft; and now, how abhorred in my imagination it is! Where be your<br>gibes now? your gambols? your songs? your flashes of merriment, that<br>were wont to set the table on a roar? Not one now, to mock your own<br>grinning? Quite chap-fallen? Now get you to my lady's chamber, and<br>tell her, let her paint an inch thick, to this favour<a href='#footnote-26' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>26</sup></a> she must<br>come; make her laugh at that. Prithee, Horatio, tell me one thing."},{character:"horatio",line:"What's that, my lord?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Dost thou think Alexander look'd o'this fashion i'the earth?"},{character:"horatio",line:"E'en so."},{character:"hamlet",line:"And smelt so? pah!<br>[Gives the skull to HORATIO, who returns it to the grave-digger.]"},{character:"horatio",line:"E'en so, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"To what base uses may we return, Horatio! Why may not<br>imagination trace the noble dust of Alexander, till it find it<br>stopping a bung-hole?"},{character:"horatio",line:"'Twere to consider too curiously,<a href='#footnote-27' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>27</sup></a> to consider so."},{character:"hamlet",line:"No, faith, not a jot; but to follow him thither with modesty<br>enough, and likelihood to lead it: As thus; Alexander died, Alexander<br>was buried, Alexander returneth to dust; the dust is earth; of earth<br>we make loam; And why of that loam, whereto he was converted, might<br>they not stop a beer barrel?<br>Imperial Cæsar,<a href='#footnote-28' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>28</sup></a> dead and turn'd to clay,<br>Might stop a hole to keep the wind away:<br>O, that the earth, which kept the world in awe,<br>Should patch a wall to expel the winter's flaw!<a href='#footnote-29' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>29</sup></a><br>But soft! but soft! aside: Here comes the king,<br>The queen, the courtiers: Who is this they follow?<br>And with such maimèd rites?<a href='#footnote-30' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>30</sup></a> This doth betoken<br>The corse they follow did with desperate hand<br>Fordo its own life:<a href='#footnote-31' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>31</sup></a> 'Twas of some estate.<a href='#footnote-32' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>32</sup></a><br>Couch we awhile, and mark."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Retiring with HORATIO, right hand] Enter Priests, &c., in procession; the corpse of OPHELIA, LAERTES and Mourners following; KING, QUEEN, their Trains, &c."},{character:"laertes",line:"(left of the grave.)<br>What ceremony else?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(right) That is Laertes,<br>A very noble youth."},{character:"firstpriest",line:"(right of the grave.)<br>Her obsequies have been as far enlarg'd<br>As we have warranty: Her death was doubtful;<br>And, but that great command o'ersways the order,<a href='#footnote-33' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>33</sup></a><br>She should in ground unsanctified have lodged<br>Till the last trumpet; for charitable prayers,<br>Shards,<a href='#footnote-34' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>34</sup></a> flints, and pebbles, should be thrown on her:<br>Yet here she is allowed her virgin crants,<a href='#footnote-35' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>35</sup></a><br>Her maiden strewments, and the bringing home<br>Of bell and burial.<a href='#footnote-36' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>36</sup></a>"},{character:"laertes",line:"Must there no more be done?"},{character:"firstpriest",line:"No more be done:<br>We should profane the service of the dead<br>To sing a requiem,<a href='#footnote-37' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>37</sup></a> and such rest to her<br>As to peace-parted souls."},{character:"laertes",line:"O, from her fair and unpolluted flesh<br>May violets spring! I tell thee, churlish priest,<a href='#footnote-38' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>38</sup></a><br>A ministering angel shall my sister be,<br>When thou liest howling."},{character:"hamlet",line:"What, the fair Ophelia!"},{character:"queen",line:"(Behind the grave, center with the KING.)<br>Sweets to the sweet: Farewell! [Scattering flowers.]<br>I hop'd thou shouldst have been my Hamlet's wife;<br>I thought thy bride-bed to have deck'd, sweet maid,<br>And not have strew'd thy grave."},{character:"laertes",line:"O, treble woe<br>Fall ten times treble on that cursed head,<br>Whose wicked deed thy most ingenious sense<a href='#footnote-39' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>39</sup></a><br>Depriv'd thee of!&mdash;Hold off the earth a while,<br>Till I have caught her once more in mine arms: [Leaps into the grave.]<br>Now pile your dust upon the quick and dead,<br>Till of this flat a mountain you have made,<br>To o'ertop old Pelion,<a href='#footnote-40' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>40</sup></a> or the skyish head<br>Of blue Olympus."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(Advancing.) What is he whose grief<br>Bears such an emphasis?&mdash;whose phrase of sorrow<br>Conjures the wand'ring stars, and makes them stand<br>Like wonder-wounded hearers?&mdash;this is I,<br>Hamlet the Dane."},{character:"laertes",line:"(left, leaping from the grave.)<br>The devil take thy soul! [Grappling with him.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(right center) Thou pray'st not well.<br>I prithee, take thy fingers from my throat;<br>For, though I am not splenetive and rash,<br>Yet have I in me something dangerous,<br>Which let thy wisdom fear: Hold off thy hand!"},{character:"king",line:"Pluck them asunder."},{character:"queen",line:"(center) Hamlet, Hamlet!"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(right center) Why, I will fight with him upon this theme<br>Until my eyelids will no longer wag."},{character:"queen",line:"O my son, what theme?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"I lov'd Ophelia: forty thousand brothers<br>Could not, with all their quantity of love,<br>Make up my sum.&mdash;What wilt thou do for her?"},{character:"queen",line:"O, he is mad, Laertes."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Come, show me what thou'lt do:<br>Wou'lt weep? wou'lt fight? wou'lt fast? wou'lt tear thyself?<br>I'll do't.&mdash;Dost thou come here to whine?<br>To outface me<a href='#footnote-41' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>41</sup></a> with leaping in her grave?<br>Be buried quick with her, and so will I:<br>And, if thou prate of mountains, let them throw<br>Millions of acres on us, till our ground,<a href='#footnote-42' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>42</sup></a><br>Singeing his pate against the burning zone,<br>Make Ossa<a href='#footnote-43' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>43</sup></a> like a wart! Nay, an thou'lt mouth,<br>I'll rant as well as thou."},{character:"queen",line:"This is mere madness:<br>And thus a while the fit will work on him;<br>Anon, as patient as the female dove,<br>When that her golden couplets are disclos'd,<a href='#footnote-44' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>44</sup></a><br>His silence will sit drooping."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Hear you, sir;<br>What is the reason that you use me thus?<br>I lov'd you ever: But it is no matter;<br>Let Hercules himself do what he may,<br>The cat will mew,<a href='#footnote-45' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>45</sup></a> and dog will have his day. [Exit, right hand]"},{character:"king",line:"(center) I pray thee, good Horatio, wait upon him. [Exit HORATIO, right hand]<br>Good Gertrude, set some watch over your son, [Exit QUEEN, attended, right hand]<br>Strengthen your patience in our last night's speech;<a href='#footnote-46' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>46</sup></a> [To LAERTES.]<br>We'll put the matter to the present push.&mdash;<br>This grave shall have a living monument:<a href='#footnote-47' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>47</sup></a><br>An hour of quiet shortly shall we see;<br>Till then, in patience our proceeding be."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[The characters group round the grave.]"}]},{scene:2,name:"Scene II",setting:"A hall in the castle.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:"Enter HAMLET and HORATIO (right hand)"},{character:"hamlet",line:"But I am very sorry, good Horatio,<br>That to Laertes I forgot myself;<br>For by the image of my cause,<a href='#footnote-48' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>48</sup></a> I see<br>The portraiture of his."},{character:"horatio",line:"Peace! who comes here? Enter OSRIC (left hand)"},{character:"osric",line:"Your lordship is right welcome back to Denmark."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) I humbly thank you, sir.&mdash;Dost know this water-fly?<a href='#footnote-49' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>49</sup></a>"},{character:"horatio",line:"(right) No, my good lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Thy state is the more gracious; for 'tis a vice to know him."},{character:"osric",line:"(left) Sweet lord, if your lordship were at leisure, I should<br>impart a thing to you from his majesty."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I will receive it, sir, with all diligence of spirit.<a href='#footnote-50' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>50</sup></a> Your<br>bonnet to his right use; 'tis for the head."},{character:"osric",line:"I thank your lordship, 'tis very hot."},{character:"hamlet",line:"No, believe me, 'tis very cold; the wind is northerly."},{character:"osric",line:"It is indifferent cold, my lord, indeed."},{character:"hamlet",line:"But yet, methinks it is very sultry and hot,<a href='#footnote-51' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>51</sup></a> for my<br>complexion,&mdash;"},{character:"osric",line:"Exceedingly, my lord; it is very sultry, as 'twere,&mdash;I cannot<br>tell how.&mdash;But, my lord, his majesty bade me signify to you, that he<br>has laid a great wager on your head: Sir, this is the matter,&mdash;"},{character:"hamlet",line:"I beseech you, remember&mdash;&mdash;<br>[HAMLET moves him to put on his hat.]"},{character:"osric",line:"Nay, good my lord; for mine ease, in good faith.<a href='#footnote-52' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>52</sup></a> Sir, here<br>is newly come to court Laertes; believe me, an absolute gentleman,<br>full of most excellent differences, of very soft society and great<br>showing:<a href='#footnote-53' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>53</sup></a> Indeed, to speak feelingly of him,<a href='#footnote-54' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>54</sup></a> he is the card or<br>calendar of gentry,<a href='#footnote-55' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>55</sup></a> for you shall find in him the continent of<br>what part a gentleman would see.<a href='#footnote-56' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>56</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"What imports the nomination of this gentleman?<a href='#footnote-57' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>57</sup></a>"},{character:"osric",line:"Of Laertes?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Of him, sir."},{character:"osric",line:"Sir, you are not ignorant of what excellence Laertes is&mdash;"},{character:"hamlet",line:"I dare not confess that, lest I should compare with him in<br>excellence; but, to know a man well, were to know himself.<a href='#footnote-58' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>58</sup></a>"},{character:"osric",line:"I mean, sir, for his weapon."},{character:"hamlet",line:"What is his weapon?"},{character:"osric",line:"Rapier and dagger."},{character:"hamlet",line:"That's two of his weapons: but, well."},{character:"osric",line:"The king, sir, hath wagered with him six Barbary horses:<br>against the which he has imponed,<a href='#footnote-59' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>59</sup></a> as I take it, six French<br>rapiers and poignards, with their assigns, as girdle, hangers,<a href='#footnote-60' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>60</sup></a> or<br>so: Three of the carriages, in faith, are very dear to fancy, very<br>responsive to the hilts, most delicate carriages, and of very liberal conceit.<a href='#footnote-61' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>61</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"What call you the carriages?"},{character:"osric",line:"The carriages, sir, are the hangers."},{character:"hamlet",line:"The phrase would be more german<a href='#footnote-62' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>62</sup></a> to the matter, if we could<br>carry cannon by our sides."},{character:"osric",line:"The king, sir, hath laid, that in a dozen passes between<br>yourself and him, he shall not exceed you three hits; and it would<br>come to immediate trial, if your lordship would vouchsafe the answer.<a href='#footnote-63' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>63</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"How if I answer no?<a href='#footnote-64' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>64</sup></a>"},{character:"osric",line:"I mean, my lord, the opposition of your person in trial."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Sir, it is the breathing time of day with me; let the foils be<br>brought, the gentleman willing, and the king hold his purpose, I will<br>win for him if I can; if not, I will gain nothing but my shame and<br>the odd hits."},{character:"osric",line:"Shall I deliver you so?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"To this effect, sir; after what flourish your nature will."},{character:"osric",line:"I commend my duty to your lordship. [Exit, left hand]"},{character:"horatio",line:"(right) You will lose this wager, my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) I do not think so; since he went into France, I have been<br>in continual practice; I shall win at the odds.<a href='#footnote-65' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>65</sup></a> But thou wouldst<br>not think how ill all's here about my heart: but it is no matter."},{character:"horatio",line:"Nay, good my lord."},{character:"hamlet",line:"It is but foolery; but it is such a kind of gain-giving,<a href='#footnote-66' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>66</sup></a><br>as would, perhaps, trouble a woman."},{character:"horatio",line:"If your mind dislike any thing, obey it:<a href='#footnote-67' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>67</sup></a> I will forestall<br>their repair hither, and say, you are not fit."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Not a whit, we defy augury: there is a special providence in<br>the fall of a sparrow."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Exeunt, left hand]"}]},{scene:3,name:"Scene III",setting:"A room in the castle.",lines:[{character:"stage_instructions",line:"KING and QUEEN, on a dais, LAERTES (right), LORDS (right), LADIES (left), OSRIC (right) and Attendants, with Foils, &c., discovered (right hand); Tables (right and left)&mdash; Flourish of Trumpets. Enter HAMLET and HORATIO (left hand)"},{character:"king",line:"Come, Hamlet, come, and take this hand from<br>me."},{character:"hamlet",line:"(offering his hand to LAERTES) Give me your<br>pardon, sir: I have done you wrong;<br>But pardon it, as you are a gentleman.<br>Let my disclaiming from a purpos'd evil<br>Free me so far in your most generous thoughts,<br>That I have shot my arrow o'er the house,<br>And hurt my brother."},{character:"laertes",line:"(right) I am satisfied in nature,<br>Whose motive, in this case, should stir me most<br>To my revenge.<br>I do receive your offer'd love like love,<br>And will not wrong it."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I embrace it freely:<br>And will this brother's wager frankly play.<br>Give us the foils."},{character:"laertes",line:"Come, one for me."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I'll be your foil, Laertes: in mine ignorance<br>Your skill shall, like a star i'the darkest night,<br>Stick fiery off indeed.<a href='#footnote-68' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>68</sup></a>"},{character:"laertes",line:"You mock me, sir."},{character:"hamlet",line:"No, by this hand."},{character:"king",line:"Give them the foils, young Osric. Cousin Hamlet,<br>You know the wager?"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Very well, my lord;<br>Your grace hath laid the odds o'the weaker side."},{character:"king",line:"I do not fear it; I have seen you both:<br>But since he's better'd,<a href='#footnote-69' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>69</sup></a> we have therefore odds."},{character:"laertes",line:"This is too heavy, let me see another."},{character:"hamlet",line:"This likes me well. These foils have all a length?"},{character:"osric",line:"Ay, my good lord."},{character:"king",line:"Set me the stoups of wine<a href='#footnote-70' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>70</sup></a> upon that table.&mdash; [Pages exeunt right and left]<br>If Hamlet give the first or second hit,<br>Or quit<a href='#footnote-71' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>71</sup></a> in answer to the third exchange,<br>Let all the battlements their ordnance fire;<br>The king shall drink to Hamlet's better breath;<br>And in the cup an union shall he throw,<a href='#footnote-72' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>72</sup></a><br>Richer than that which four successive kings<br>In Denmark's crown have worn. [Pages return with wine.] Give me the cup;<br>And let the kettle<a href='#footnote-73' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>73</sup></a> to the trumpet speak,<br>The trumpet to the cannoneer without,<br>The cannons to the heavens, the heaven to earth,<br>Now the king drinks to Hamlet.&mdash;Come, begin;<br>And you, the judges, bear a wary eye."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Come on, sir."},{character:"laertes",line:"Come, my lord. [They play.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"One."},{character:"laertes",line:"No."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Judgment."},{character:"osric",line:"A hit, a very palpable hit."},{character:"laertes",line:"Well:&mdash;again."},{character:"king",line:"Stay; give me drink. Hamlet, this pearl is thine; [Drops poison into the goblet.]<br>Here's to thy health. [Pretends to drink.] [Trumpets sound; and cannon shot off within.]<br>Give him the cup."},{character:"hamlet",line:"I'll play this bout first; set it by awhile. [Page places the goblet on table, left]<br>Come.<br>Another hit; What say you? [They play.]"},{character:"laertes",line:"A touch, a touch, I do confess."},{character:"king",line:"Our son shall win."},{character:"queen",line:"The Queen carouses to thy fortune, Hamlet.<a href='#footnote-74' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>74</sup></a>"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Good madam!&mdash;&mdash; [Trumpets sound.]"},{character:"king",line:"Gertrude, do not drink."},{character:"queen",line:"I have, my lord; I pray you, pardon me."},{character:"king",line:"It is the poison'd cup; it is too late. [Aside.]"},{character:"laertes",line:"I'll hit him now<br>And yet it is almost against my conscience. [Aside.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"Come, for the third, Laertes: You do but dally;<br>I pray you, pass with your best violence;<br>I am afeard you make a wanton of me.<a href='#footnote-75' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>75</sup></a>"},{character:"laertes",line:"Say you so? come on. [They play.] [LAERTES wounds HAMLET; then, in scuffling they change Rapiers, and HAMLET wounds LAERTES.]"},{character:"king",line:"Part them; they are incensed."},{character:"hamlet",line:"Nay, come, again. [The QUEEN falls back in her chair.]"},{character:"osric",line:"(Supporting LAERTES, right)<br>Look to the queen there, ho!"},{character:"horatio",line:"(Supporting HAMLET, left)<br>How is it, my lord?"},{character:"osric",line:"How is't, Laertes?"},{character:"laertes",line:"Why, as a woodcock to my own springe,<a href='#footnote-76' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>76</sup></a> Osric;<br>I am justly killed with mine own treachery."},{character:"hamlet",line:"How does the queen?"},{character:"king",line:"She swoons to see them bleed."},{character:"queen",line:"No, no, the drink, the drink,&mdash;O, my dear Hamlet,&mdash;<br>The drink, the drink! I am poison'd. [The QUEEN is conveyed off the stage by her attendant Ladies, in a dying state, left hand upper entrance]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"O villainy! Ho! let the doors be lock'd:<br>Treachery! seek it out. [LAERTES falls.]"},{character:"laertes",line:"(right) It is here, Hamlet: Hamlet, thou art slain;<br>No medicine in the world can do thee good,<br>In thee there is not half an hour's life;<br>The treacherous instrument is in thy hand,<br>Unbated and envenom'd:<a href='#footnote-77' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>77</sup></a> the foul practice<a href='#footnote-78' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>78</sup></a><br>Hath turn'd itself on me; lo, here I lie,<br>Never to rise again: Thy mother's poison'd:<br>I can no more: the king, the king's to blame."},{character:"hamlet",line:"The point<br>Envenom'd too! Then, venom, to thy work.<br>Here, thou incestuous, murd'rous, damnèd Dane,<br>Follow my mother. [Stabs the KING, who is borne away by his attendants, mortally wounded, right hand upper entrance]"},{character:"laertes",line:"He is justly serv'd;<br>Exchange forgiveness with me, noble Hamlet:<br>Mine and my father's death come not upon thee,<br>Nor thine on me! [Dies.]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"(center) Heaven make thee free of it! I follow thee.<br>You that look pale and tremble at this chance,<br>That are but mutes or audience to this act,<br>Had I but time (as this fell sergeant, death,<a href='#footnote-79' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>79</sup></a><br>Is strict in his arrest), O, I could tell you,&mdash;<br>But let it be. Horatio,<br>Report me and my cause aright<br>To the unsatisfied."},{character:"horatio",line:"(left) Never believe it:<br>I am more an antique Roman than a Dane:<br>Here's yet some liquor left. [Seizing the goblet on table, left]"},{character:"hamlet",line:"As thou'rt a man,&mdash;<br>Give me the cup: let go; by heaven, I'll have it. [Dashes the goblet away.]<br>O good Horatio, what a wounded name,<br>Things standing thus unknown, shall live behind me!<a href='#footnote-80' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>80</sup></a><br>If thou didst ever hold me in thy heart,<br>Absènt thee from felicity awhile,<br>And in this harsh world draw thy breath in pain,<br>To tell my story.&mdash;<br>O, I die, Horatio;<br>The potent poison quite o'er-crows my spirit;<a href='#footnote-81' rel='bookmark' class='footnote__link'><sup>81</sup></a><br>The rest is silence."},{character:"stage_instructions",line:"[Dies, center, OSRIC on his right, and HORATIO on his left] Dead March afar off. Curtain slowly descends."}]}]}];